column12: Improvements in Type Mechanism for Time Record Printing Machines.
column13: 10,232. Duncan, J. May 16. Time-checking apparatus for workmen. Relates to the type-wheel mechanism of workmen's timerecorders and the like. Units' and tens' minuteprinting wheels 1, 2, Figs. 1 and 2, and an hourprinting wheel 3, are provided, on a spindle 7. The wheel 1 is fast on the spindle 7, and is driven continuously through a loose pinion 5 and a connexion comprising two lugs 10 on a wheel 8, fixed to the wheel 1, and an arm 9, fixed to the pinion 5. One lug 10 is maintained against the arm 9 by means of a spring 12, and the wheel 1 has freedom of movement limited by the second lug. The wheel 2 is fast on a sleeve 18, geared to a spindle 15, driven from two teeth 13 on the wheel 8 through a pinion 14. The teeth 13 are at twenty-tooth pitch, and the space between them is cut away across the rim of the wheel 8. The pinion 14 has eight teeth, alternately long and short, and two of the long teeth lock against the rim of the wheel 8, except when the teeth 13 co-operate. The wheel 3 is similarly driven by means of a toothed wheel 19, a loose pinion 23, and a wheel 20 having two pairs of teeth 21, 22. The type-wheel gearing allows of forward and backward rotation for setting the bands of the clock. The spindle 15 is mounted in bearings 26 in adjustable pieces 27, Figs. 2 and 4, pivoted on screws 28 and secured by pins 29. Alinement of the wheel 1 is obtained by means of a ratchet-wheel 30, Figs. 1, 2, and 4, and a pawl 37 on a lever 31, limited by a stop 41. The pawl 37 is on a pivoted piece 36 retained by a spring 43, The lever 31 is, normally, held away from the ratchet-wheel, against the action of a spring 33, by means of a rod 46, which 'is provided with an adjustable block 44, engaging with a pin 42 on the lever 31, and is slotted at the outer end over a pin 49, attached to a part having a motion suitable for bringing the pin 49 towards the lever 31 when alinement is required. Should the lever 31 be held in, the arm 9 will overtake the lug 10, the ratchetwheel 30 will run over the pawl 37, and the clock will not be stopped. receiver 3 projects through a slot in the top plate of the case, and has fixed to its front a plate with letters corresponding with those at the top of the card columns. The card receiver can be adjusted and locked in the required position. A bell 44 is rung when printing occurs, but not when the anvil 6 is struck. In a modified machine, the safety device comprising the anvil 6, the bent lever 5, and the transmission mechanism between these parts may be omitted.

The driving - clock, the type-wheels and the method of driving them, and the inking-arrangements are ordinary. If the card 1 is not in its proper position in the receiver 3, the anvil 6 instead of the card takes the blow of the printing- hammer 31. This is effected through the bent lever 5, mounted on the card platform 4 being allowed to move too far, past the lower edge of the card, so raising the anvil 6 into position to receive the hammer blow. The transmission mechanism between the card platform and the anvil comprises a crank 18 on the spindle 15, forming the pivot of the lever 5, and a rod 20, and cranks 21. The card receiver 3 has free horizontal movement by means of a slide on the guide-rods 8. The card platform 4 is guided vertically on the rods 12, and is raised at definite intervals by mechanism controlled by the clock. A projecting piece on the platform 4 rests on the upper edge of a lifting-frame 52, which . is raised by the chain 56 secured to the pulley 59. This pulley runs loose on the spindle 60, and is driven by the disk 61. The spindle 60 is operated once in twelve hours ; and every half revolution of a two-toothed wheel 72 passes one of fourteen slots in the wheel 70 and rotates the chain-pulley 59 through one-fourteenth of a revolution. column12: Improvements in Ink Ribbon Driving Gears.
column13: 10,228. Duncan, J. May 16. Time-checking apparatus for workmen. Relates to an automatically-reversible driving-gear for the - ink-ribbons of typewriting-machines, time-recording machines, and the like. One end of the ribbon is attached to a reel D which can be driven in either direction by means of a mitre wheel, which can gear with either of twowheels B<1>, B<2> on a shaft S, intermittently rotated by a ratchet-wheel W and pawl or other means. The other end of the ribbon is attached to a reel T, to the spindle V of which is fixed one end of a spring 0 which tends to wind the ribbon on to the reel T. To prevent the reel D from being rotated by the pull of the spring 0, the reel is braked by the action of a spring S<2> which presses the boss of the wheel B<3> against the framework, The feed of the ribbon is reversed by means of a lever L, mounted on a pivot 2 and having a forked end which rests between two collars 4 on the shaft S. The lever L is held in its extreme positions by locking-levers L<1>, which can engage with pins P on the lever L and are pulled towards each other by a spring L<2>. In line with the spindle of the reel D is mounted a spindle R carrying a mitre wheel B<4> which can gear with either of the wheels B<1>, B<3>. The spindle R is threaded and on it travels a block B, to which is secured a rod 7 having slotted ends which engage with pins 8, 9 on the levers L<1>. The lever L is provided with forked arms 10 which embrace the spindle R, and between the block B and the arms 10 are placed springs 12, 13. When the block B reaches the upper or lower limit of its travel on the spindle R, the rod 7 moves the locking-lever L<1> which is in engagement with its pin P, and one of the springs 12, 13 rocks the lever L. The shaft S is thereby moved longitudinally and the feed of the ribbon is reversed.

column13: 16. Duncan, J. G., and Duncan, R. Jan. 1. Cooking-ranges; ovens; flues.-Relates to the construction and arrangement of oven - heating flues for cooking-ranges of the kind in which the bottom of the oven is at a higher level than the grate. The flue A, which leads from the fire-grate to the middle of the space beneath the oven, is surrounded by an air-beating jacket a<4>, preferably divided by partitions a<7>. The hot air passes through openings a<8> formed by the toothed upper edge of the flue A, and, mingling with the gases from the fire, ensures more complete combustion. The hot gases impinge upon a fire-clay or metal casting b<4>, which is domed,. conical, or pyramidal in shape. The casting may be formed in one with the bottom of the oven, or may be removably fitted in a flanged hole, as shown in Fig. 2. A coned ring may be fitted above the openings a<8> to deflect the air and the products of combustion upon the casting. In a modified form, the air-heating jacket is omitted,

column12: Improvements in and Relating to Collapsable Wheel Barrows and Similar Vehicles.
column13: 23,701. Duncan, J., and Baird, J. Nov. 22. Hand-trucks; wheelbarrows.-Relates to collapsable wheelbarrows and similar vehicles, one form being shown in a partially-collapsed state in Figs. 1 and 2. The two rigid side frames A are connected together at the front by two stays B, which are pivoted to the side frames and to one another, preferably by hinged links b<1>. Similar stays connect the back ends of the frames and two intermediate points, but the intermediate stays B', which are normally held extended by a pivoted bar b<3>,. collapse in a horizontal plane, and the end stays in vertical planes. The parts C of the axle are pivoted together at B<2>, b<2>, to allow the axle to collapse in a horizontal plane, and sleeves C<2> are pinned over the joints when the parts are extended. When the front and rear stays are extended, detachable bars may be fitted over them, and may be held in position by bent clips and spring catches. The floor of the vehicle consists of boards D hinged at D' to the side frames and normally held down either by sliding bolts D<2> or by the detachable bars.

column13: A convertible tray 101 comprises a substantially planar rigid base portion 104 and a border 105 extending around the base portion 104. column13: A bristle head for an electric toothbrush has a casing, a drive shaft within the casing and a flexible membrane mounted to or formed integrally with the casing. A number of bristle tufts extend from the flexible membrane and roots of each tuft extend into the casing. A transmission is provided for transmitting movement of the drive shaft to the roots of the bristle tufts whereupon the flexible membrane flexes as or the bristle tufts move. The design prevents toothpaste and other liquid from entering into the casing where it might wear moving parts and harbour bacteria.

column12: Improvements Relating to Abandonment and Recovery of Pipelines
column13: A method of abandoning a pipeline during subsea pipelaying from a pipelay vessel includes suspending the pipe string from a tendon element of an abandonment string and engaging further tendon elements to an upper end of the abandonment string while lowering the pipe string to a handover depth. At the handover depth, tension is applied via a wire to the top of the pipe string at an acute angle to the launch axis. This deflects the pipe string from the launch axis into axial alignment with the wire to transfer the weight load of the pipe string to the wire, whereupon the abandonment string can be decoupled from the pipe string. Recovery of the pipeline from the seabed can be effected by a reverse process.

Implement adapter for an excavation tool assembly
column13: An implement adapter for providing improved excavation versatility that couples with and attaches to an excavation tool assembly for mounting a working implement thereon. The implement adapter comprises a frame for holding a working implement, wherein the frame is coupled and semi-fixedly attached to an excavation tool assembly. A parking projection holds the coupling element of the frame at a sufficient height above a surface when the implement adapter is detached from the excavation tool assembly and supported on the surface by the parking projection and a lowermost portion of either the frame or the working implement. The height at which the coupling portion is held by the parking projection enables engagement of the coupling portion with a cooperative coupling element on the excavation tool assembly without the need for any manual assistance. Additionally, the implement adapter is capable of mounting upon various sizes of excavation tools and articulating attached working implements in multiple ranges of motion.

column12: Method of welding a heating element to a vessel for forming a heating container
column13: An electric heating element having a central conductor and an outer metallic sheath is welded to a base of vessel to provide a heating container, for hot water in a domestic appliance for example. In order to carry out the welding, the vessel is heated up by an induction heater to a certain temperature and the temperature of the actual contacting welding surfaces raised above the certain temperature to a fusing temperature by applying and controlling electric power supplied to the conductor while the heating element is held firmly in position against the base.

Embodiments provide methods and systems for modeling a proposed geological volume. One such embodiment begins by digitally creating a three-dimensional (3D) model of a geological volume that includes one or more variables, each of which is a mathematical factor in an analysis confidence of one or more sub-volumes of the volume. Next, standardized values for each of the one or more variables are defined. In turn, the analysis confidence, e.g. mined, ore quality, etc., of the one or more sub-volumes is mathematically determined. Finally, the model is updated to include the determined analysis confidence of the one or more sub-volumes.

A package of tape including a plurality of body portions. Each body portion is formed as a series of steps, each step including a plurality of turns of tape that are wrapped about a core. During formation of each step, the winding position of the tape is varied. In one embodiment, the winding position of the tape is oscillated a fraction of the width of the tape per revolution of the core, or during a revolution of the core. In an alternative embodiment, the winding position of the tape is varied by a fraction of the width of the tape in a first direction after each approximately full turn of tape. During formation of an immediately adjacent step in the same body portion, the winding position of the tape is varied by a fraction of the width of the tape in a second direction, opposite the first direction.

A gas water heating system is described that utilises most of the heat of combustion of the fuel in an area remote from the tank itself. It also provides a cold lower tank area that stays cooler than the bulk of the volume of the tank through the heating cycle. It also provides a cold lower tank area above the flue outlet of the remote heat exchanger further enhancing the efficiency. It also delivers hotter water to the top of the tank, thereby filling the tank with hot water from the top down. It also utilises the superior insulating properties of plastic foam. It also efficiently uses the pilot flame heat without it causing a high airflow through the unit, with attendant thermal losses. The tank unit is easily replaced in the event of a tank leak or rupture, but retaining the gas equipment and heat exchanger for further use. The central flue has been deleted, and the products of combustion are now directed up the outside of the tank surface in a gap provided between the tank outer wall and a metal sheet wrap to keep the hot gases against the tank wall. Two or more separate fluid paths that are in good mutual contact for efficient heat transfer. The fluid paths are generally tubular and the length of the tubing on one side of the heat exchanger carrying a first fluid may be shorter or longer than that for the second fluid. Ko E ..u9

An elongate sling section is disclosed. The elongate sling is cooperable with like sling sections to form a sling for use in abandonment or recovery of a pipeline. The sling section includes end-pieces at five opposite ends and complementary connector formations associated with each respective end-piece. Each connector formation is cooperable, in use when forming a sling, with a complementary connector formation of a neighbouring sling section in the sling. The sling section further includes a tensile load-bearing sling element extending between the end-pieces and a sleeve around the sling element.

column13: Cell-based gene transfer is effected by administering transfected cells containing an expressible transgene into the pulmonary system of a patient, where the cells express and secrete expression products of the transgene directly into the pulmonary system. Also provided is the use of angiogenic factors in treatment of pulmonary hypertension.

An electrical pressure sensing switch for a pressure cooker comprises a plunger slidably and sealingly mounted in a lid 21 of a cooking vessel 20. The plunger 24 is moved towards one end of a pivoted lever 33 when pressure rises inside the vessel 20. The other end of the lever is positioned to press down against an operating arm 26. When the force applied by the plunger as a result of higher pressures in the vessel 20 is sufficient to overcome bias of a spring 28, the arm 26 is moved down by the lever. This results in operation of micro-switches 31 and 32. Embodiments of the invention are mechanically simple and accommodate wide tolerances without loss of calibration, while necessary electrical parts are separated or separable from the lid 21 to facilitate cleaning and washing.

A vacuum coffee maker has a starved electric heating arrangement having a solid body providing a reservoir. The chamber is covered by a circular lid that prevents flow of steam directly vertically up a tube from the chamber. At the end of a normal heating cycle, the temperature of the body rises rapidly and power supplied to a heating element is automatically turned off under the control of a thermostat. The heating arrangement is used without alteration (e.g. to the setting of the thermostat) to keep-warm hot coffee in a lower container after the end of the normal heating coffee-making cycle. The effect of having the lid is that during a keep-warm function, the reservoir is generally starved of liquid because any liquid entering the reservoir is immediately evaporated and this restricts flow of more liquid into the reservoir and hence starves the reservoir.

column12: Improvements in Field and Ambulance Stretchers.

column13: A dynamic clock feedback latch includes a feedback path that generates a data value on an output as a function of data inputs in response to a clock input going low and generates a latching value on the output after a delay from the clock input going high. A first transistor pre-charges a node high while the clock input is low. A second transistor provides a drain path for draining the node low from the pre-charged value while the clock input is high. The output controls a third transistor during the delay to drain the node to a low value if the data value is high and to retain the high value if the data value is low. The feedback path generates the predetermined latching value on the output after the delay to cause an inverted value of the data value to be latched onto the node.
Novel isooxazoles, oxazoles, thiazoles, isothiazoles and imidazoles, pharmaceutical compositions containing these compounds and their use as endothelin receptor antagonists are described.

A storage system for storing continuous lengths of rigid pipe, particularly for storage of pipe prior to the spooling of the pipe onto the pipe storage reel of a marine pipelay vessel. The system comprises a loop of rail track with a plurality of rail bogies arranged around the circumference of the loop. The bogies are adapted to retain and receive multiple turns of the length of pipe extending around the loop. The radius of curvature of the loop is selected such that the bending of the pipe around the loop does not result in plastic deformation of the pipe. Arrangements for loading and offloading the pipe may include: a pipe guide suspended from a gantry spanning the track and a pipe loading/offloading path; pipe tensioning means located downstream of the pipe guide in the offloading direction; and an "expansion arc" extending from the loading/offloading point to allow variations in the length of the pipeline path extending from the loop to a vessel mooring location.

A device for protecting plumbing fittings from hydraulic over-pressure pulses or shock (water hammer) finds particular application in solenoid diaphragm valves used in automatic washing appliances of the type in which a diaphragm (14) is held against a seat (15) by a spring-loaded plunger (16), and is opened by energising a solenoid coil (18) to raise the plunger (16) against the opposing force of spring (17). The device comprises a spring (26) which holds a plug (27) against a seat (28) so blocking an orifice (29) against normal pressure difference between high and low pressure compartments (19, 20). When hydraulic shock pressure front enters the valve (10), it moves the plug (27) away from the seat (28) to allow a small volume of water from the high pressure compartment (19) to be expelled through the orifice (29) thus dissipating shock.

column12: Cell-based therapy for the pulmonary system
column13: Cell based therapy comprises administration to the lung by injection into the blood system of viable, mammalian cells effective for alleviating or inhibiting pulmonary disorders. The cells may express a therapeutic transgene or the cells may be therapeutic in their own right by inducing regenerative effects.

column13: A system for transporting a pig (28) along the interior of a pipeline (26), particularly for the purpose of installing a liner (12) in the pipeline by towing the liner behind the pig, in which a hydrostatic head is applied on either side of the pig and the head on the downstream side of the pig is reduced such that the pig is transported along the interior of the pipeline by the resultant pressure differential. Where the system is employed in a pre-existing subsea pipeline, the hydrostatic heads may be applied by means of risers (14, 24) and the pressure differential created by means of a pump (30) adapted to pump water out of the downstream riser (24). The liner may be pulled through a flooded pipe by means of a pig, cable, self-propelled pipe crawler, or by combinations of these. A further cable may also be employed to apply a back tension, and/or to limit the pulling force applied to the liner and/or to enable the liner to be pulled backwards.

column13: This invention relates to a bolt arrangement suitable for use as a locking bolt (20) or latching bolt of a mortise lock, or to a locking bolt for use in a double action security lock. The bolt arrangement includes an actuating section (21), in use being slideably displaceable inside the lock, and a bolt section (22) for selectively engaging an external structure. column13: An electric heating element having a central conductor 10 and an outer metallic sheath 11 is welded to a base 13 of vessel 12 to provide a heating container, for hot water in a domestic appliance for example. A storage system for storing continuous lengths of rigid pipe, particularly for storage of pipe prior to the spooling of the pipe onto the pipe storage reel of a marine pipelay vessel. The system comprises a loop (12) of rail track (20) with a plurality of rail bogies (100) arranged around the circumference of the loop (12). The bogies (100) are adapted to retain and receive multiple turns of the length of pipe (102) extending around the loop (12). The radius of curvature of the loop (12) is selected such that the bending of the pipe (102) around the loop (12) does not result in plastic deformation of the pipe (102). Arrangements for loading and offloading the pipe (102) may include: a pipe guide (232) suspended from a gantry (230) spanning the track (20) and a pipe loading/offloading path (238); pipe tensioning means (234) located downstream of the pipe guide (232) in the offloading direction; and an 'expansion arc' (216) extending from the loading/offloading point to allow variations in the length of the pipeline path (238) extending from the loop (12) to a vessel mooring location.

column12: COMMUNICATION DEVICE HAVING A WIDEBAND RECEIVER AND OPERATING METHOD THEREFOR
column13: To accommodate for a release of uncleared spectrum in a wideband communication system (10) while improving isolation in a receiver (FIG. 4) between wideband carriers, a common intermediate frequency converter down-converts differing but relatively high frequency carriers, incident to the receiver, to corresponding differing but relatively low frequency carriers. Receiver chains (174-176) response to the plurality of relatively low frequency carriers each have a filter (140-144) arranged to isolate selected ones of the relatively low frequency carriers. In a radio frequency communication system having three or more frequency sequential carriers, the receiver chains (174-176) may include branches that have filters that further isolate carriers within the receiver by applying non-sequential carriers to the branches in each receiver chain.

column13: An elongate sling (28) section is cooperable with like sling sections (28) to form a sling for use in abandonment or recovery of a pipeline. The sling section comprises end-pieces (34, 36) at 5 opposite ends and complementary connector formations (38, 40) associated with each respective end-piece (34, 36). Each connector formation (38, 40) is cooperable, in use when forming a sling, with a complementary connector formation of a neighbouring sling section (28) in the sling. The sling section further comprises a tensile load-bearing sling element (30) extending between the end-pieces (34, 36); and a sleeve (32) around the sling element (30).

column12: Implement adapter for an excavation tool assembly
column13: An implement adapter for providing excavation versatility that couples with and attaches to an excavation tool assembly for mounting a working implement thereon. The implement adapter comprises a frame for holding a working implement, wherein the frame is coupled and semi-fixedly attached to an excavation tool assembly. A parking projection holds the coupling element of the frame at a sufficient height above a surface when the implement adapter is detached from the excavation tool assembly and supported on the surface by the parking projection and a lowermost portion of either the frame or the working implement. The height at which the coupling portion is held by the parking projection enables engagement of the coupling portion with a cooperative coupling element on the excavation tool assembly without the need for any manual assistance. Additionally, the implement adapter has sliding and rotating connecting elements capable of connection to various sizes of excavation tools via manual or remotely actuated fastening mechanisms.

A mouth washing device includes a handle housing a motor and a driveshaft driven by the motor. column12: Coffee machine having a grounds-compressing piston
column13: A coffee machine has a space for receiving coffee grounds. Pressurised fluid is forced into the space. There is a filter screen against which the coffee grounds bear in use and through which coffee-infused fluid from the space passes to be dispensed. A fluid-pervious piston is located within the space and moves toward the filter screen to thereby compress the coffee grounds in use. This prevents the coffee grounds from separating from one another in which case the pressurised fluid might take a path of least resistance, not necessarily an infusion path through the grounds.

A package of tape including a plurality of body portions. Each body portion is formed as a series of steps, each step including a plurality of turns of tape that are wrapped about a core. During formation of each step, the winding position of the tape is varied. In one embodiment, the winding position of the tape is oscillated a fraction of the width of the tape per revolution of the core, or during a revolution of the core. In an alternative embodiment, the winding position of the tape is varied by a fraction of the width of the tape in a first direction after each approximately full turn of tape. During formation of an immediately adjacent step in the same body portion, the winding position of the tape is varied by a fraction of the width of the tape in a second direction, opposite the first direction.

column13: método para abandonar ou recuperar uma tubulação durante o lançamento de dutos submarinos, elemento de cabo de protensão e coluna de abandono. a invenção refere-se a um método para abandonar uma tubulação durante o lançamento de dutos submarinos a partir de uma embarcação de lançamento de tubulação (28) que compreende suspender a coluna de dutos (38) a partir de um elemento de cabo de protensão (36) de uma coluna de abandono e engatar elementos de cabo de protensão adicionais (36) a uma extremidade superior da coluna de abandono enquanto abaixa a coluna de dutos (38) em uma profundidade de transmissão. na profundidade de transmissão, a tensão é aplicada através de um cabo (48) ao topo da coluna de dutos (38) em um ângulo agudo para o eixo geométrico de lançamento. isso desvia a coluna de dutos (38) a partir do eixo geométrico de lançamento em alinhamento axial com o cabo (48) a fim de transferir a carga de peso da coluna de dutos (38) para o cabo (48), em que a coluna de abandono pode ser desacoplada da coluna de dutos (38). a recuperação da tubulação a partir do fundo do mar pode ser executada por processo inverso.

column12: Improvements relating to abandonment and recovery of pipelines
column13: A method of abandoning a pipeline during subsea pipelaying from a pipelay vessel (28) comprises suspending the pipe string (38) from a tendon element (36) of an abandonment string and engaging further tendon elements (36) to an upper end of the abandonment string while lowering the pipe string (38) to a handover depth. At the handover depth, tension is applied via a wire (48) to the top of the pipe string (38) at an acute angle to the launch axis. This deflects the pipe string (38) from the launch axis into axial alignment with the wire (48) to transfer the weight load of the pipe string (38) to the wire (48), whereupon the abandonment string can be decoupled from the pipe string (38). Recovery of the pipeline from the seabed can be effected by a reverse process.

column13: A system for transporting a pig (28) along the interior of a pipeline (26), particularly for the purpose of installing a liner (12) in the pipeline by towing the liner behind the pig, in which a hydrostatic head is applied on either side of the pig and the head on the downstream side of the pig is reduced such that the pig is transported along the interior of the pipeline by the resultant pressure differential. column12: IMPROVED INDUCTION HEATING APPARATUS AND METHOD FOR PIPELINEWELDING OPERATIONS
column13: Induction heating apparatus for use in welding an end of a first length of pipe (26) to the exterior surface of a second length of pipe (28), consists of heating assemblies (20, 24) each comprising at least one electrical induction coil (32, 36) wound on an annular, laminated, magnetic core assembly (30, 34). The lowermost surfaces of said core assembly (30, 34) define a saddle shape adapted to be seated on the exterior surface of said second length of pipe (28). The arrangement of the coils (32, 36) and the core assemblies (30, 34) is such that substantially all of the magnetic flux generated when the apparatus is seated on the pipe (28) and the coil is energised is contained within the core assembly and within the wall of the pipe (28). Advantageously, the core assemblies (30, 34) have E-sections profiles, the ends of the limbs of the E-sections comprising the lowermost surfaces of the core assemblies and the coils being wound about the central limbs of the E-sections. The core assembly is formed from a plurality of part-annular segments, each segment having an individual induction coil associated therewith. The apparatus may comprise first and second heating assemblies, the first extending around the outer periphery of a circular weld zone defined on the exterior surface of said second length of pipe and the second extending around the inner periphery of the weld zone.

column12: Distortion compensation control for a power amplifier
column13: A control arrangement and method for controlling a gain and phase adjuster used for controlling the gain and phase of a compensation signal for compensating for the distortion produced by a power amplifier is disclosed. The control arrangement makes use of a reference signal, of known frequency, which is amplified along with the desired carrier signals. The reference signal component of the amplified signal is then isolated and a comparison is made, either with the actual reference signal, e.g., by a QAM demodulator, or alternatively with the known frequency of the reference signal, e.g., by a FM discriminator, in order to determine the differences in gain and in phase of the reference signal component of the amplified signal in comparison with the reference signal. For example, a QAM demodulator is used for producing a first difference signal indicative of the phase switch difference, and a second difference signal indicative of the gain switch difference. These signals are then correlated with the signal envelope of the main signal in order to produce signals indicative of the sign and magnitude of the control signals used to adjust the gain and phase adjuster in a feed back loop.

column12: Improvements in apparatus for preventing ice-formation on aircraft surfaces
column13: 1,060,390. De-icing aircraft. BRITISH AIRCRAFT CORPORATION (OPERATING) Ltd. Sept. 16, 1965 [June 23, 1964], No. 25933/64. Heading B7W. [Also in Division F1] Apparatus for de-icing aircraft comprises a small-bore tube, e.g. # inch diameter, embedded in a surface to be de-iced and connected in the circuit of an hydraulic control circuit operating at high pressure, e.g. 4000 p.s.i., whereby the heat generated by the flow of liquid through the tube is adequate to remove or prevent the formation of ice. A pump 25 delivers hydraulic oil through pipe 27 to operate flying controls and through priority valve 29 and pipe 28 to operate an undercarriage and, through a further priority valve 26 and solenoid operated valve 12, to supply oil to a small bore pipe or pipes 10 buried in a surface to be de-iced, the oil returning to a tank 32 through a pressuremaintaining valve 13, filter 36 and oil cooler 31, which are arranged in parallel with a thermostatically-controlled by-pass 33 and a pressure limiting by-pass 34. A switch 16 responsive to the differential pressure across valve 13 is connected to solenoid 22 through a normally closed manually operated switch 24 and a normally open manually operated switch 23. In operation, de-icing is initiated by closure of switch 23, the resulting presaure difference across valve 13 closing switch 16 to complete the circuit from voltage input 19 to solenoid 22, thereby permitting release of switch 23. De-icing is terminated by closure of switch 24. Should tube 10 be damaged, e.g. by impact, valves 12 and 13 would be operated automatically by a presiure-drop to isolate the de-icing part of the hydraulic circuit. Arrangements of tubes embedded in wing surfaces are described.

20,188. Duncan, J. A. Sept. 25. Shutters with pivoting blades.-In a shutter with two symmetrically pivoted blades 25<a>, 25<b>, Fig. 2, the blades are actuated by a helical spring 36<a>, 36<b> passing around and secured at its midposition 35 to a segmental member 33, Fig. 5, which is concentrically mounted relatively to the lens opening and adapted to be rotated and locked in position to put either section of the spring under tension. When the blades are free and neither spring is tensioned. the shutter is set by first moving a finger 17 along an arcuate slot 14, Fig. 1, in the front plate 1, say in a clockwise direction, thereby rotating the member 33 clockwise, tensioning the spring 36<a>, and operating the blades through the levers 28, 30<a> so that the projection 32<a> on the blade 25<a> snaps behind the retainiug-end 39<a> of the spring 38. The finger 17 is then moved in a contrary direction into the opposite sector of the slot 14 in order to tension the spring 36<b>. The shutter is released by the slide 42, which has arms 41 to retract the spring plate 38 from the projection 39<a>. The blades swing across the shutter, and the projection 32<b> on the blade 25<b> subsequently snaps behind the other end 39<b> of the spring 38. The exposure is determined by the degree of tension on the spring 36<b>, and the finger 17 is held in any position along the arcuate slot 14 by an auxiliary spring finger 19 which engages slots 16. For the next exposure the finger 17 is moved to the opposite section of the slot 14. For time exposures, a sliding catch 52 is adjusted in position to engage the lever 28 when the apertures in the blades are coincident with the lens aperture. The catch 52 is held out of position by a hook 54 when not required.

An electrical pressure sensing switch for a pressure cooker comprises a plunger slidably and sealingly mounted in a lid 21 of a cooking vessel 20. The plunger 24 is moved towards one end of a pivoted lever 33 when pressure rises inside the vessel 20. The other end of the lever is positioned to press down against an operating arm 26. When the force applied by the plunger as a result of higher pressures in the vessel 20 is sufficient to overcome bias of a spring 28, the arm 26 is moved down by the lever. This results in operation of micro-switches 31 and 32. Embodiments of the invention are mechanically simple and accommodate wide tolerances without loss of calibration, while necessary electrical parts are separated or separable from the lid 21 to facilitate cleaning and washing.

column12: Processo e aparelho para instalar um revestimento interno em um oleoduto.
column13: "PROCESSO E APARELHO PARA INSTALAR UM REVESTIMENTO INTERNO EM UM OLEODUTO". Um sistema para transportar um pistão raspador (28) ao longo do interior de um oleoduto (26), especialmente para o fim de instalar um revestimento (12) no oleoduto tracionando o revestimento por trás do pistão raspador, no qual uma carga hidrostática é aplicada num ou noutro lado do pistão raspador e a carga no lado a jusante do pistão raspador é reduzida de tal modo que o pistão raspador seja transportado ao longo do interior do oleoduto pelo diferencial de pressão resultante. Onde o sistema é empregado em um oleoduto submarino pré-existente, as cargas hidrostática podem ser aplicadas por intermédio de tubos de prolongamento (14, 24) e o diferencial de pressão criado por intermédio de uma bomba (30) adaptado para bombear água para fora do tubo de prolongamento a jusante (24). O revestimento pode ser tracionado através do tubo alagado por intermédio de um pistão raspador, trator de tubo auto-motriz, ou por combinações destes. Um outro cabo também pode ser empregado aplicar contra-tensão, e/ou limitar a força de tração aplicada ao revestimento e/ou habilitar o revestimento a ser puxado para trás.

column12: Heat exchanger with passive in-line temperature control

Embossing.-Relates to mill engraving in which the different depth of design is obtained by the more or less frequent passage of the mill over the surface of the roller or block, and consists in providing automatic mechanical means for oscillating the roller in contact with the mill. A roller A is driven by spur-wheels A<3>, A<2> from a wheel A' on a shaft a carrying a bevelwheel C<3> gearing with wheels C<1>, C<2>, either of which may be clutched to the driving-shaft B<1> by a clutch C. The clutch C is operated by a fork c, a lever L<1> pivoted at l, and a connecting-rod L, from a bell-crank k, the slotted end K of which engages a pin i<2> in a rod i<1> attached to the carriage I. The carriage I is supported by rods i which slide in the stationary end frames d<x>. Resting in notches in the ends of the carriage I are a series (in this case two) of bars H each carrying two adjustable stops G, G' adapted to be engaged by a cross-head D' carried by a rack D reciprocated by gearing F<1>, F<2>, F<3>, a shaft E<2>, bevel-gearing E, E<1>, and a shaft D<2>, from . the shaft a. The bars H when in the operative position are supported on two segments M, each provided with a notch m into which one bar H is adapted to drop out of action at a point determined by stops O on a ratchet bar N<3> fed forward by a pawl N<2>, Figs. 2 and 4. The pawl N<2> is pivoted on an eccentric pin n<2> on a catch N pivoted on a bar secured to the stationary end frame d<x>. At each movement of the cross-head D<3> to the right, a catch I<1> engages the catch N and feeds the bar N' along until the first stop O engages a stop on the segment M and rocks it, so that the first bar H drops into the notch m out of action. When the second stop O engages the segment, it is further rocked, causing the second bar to fall out of action and-leaving the clutch mechanism to be controlled by stops G<2>, G<3> on the bar H<1> of the carriage I. A weighted cord or a helical spring attached to an eye N<4> in the ratchet bar N<3> tends to return the bar N<3>, but is normally prevented from doing so by a retaining-pawl N<5>. Both the pawls N<2>, N<5> are disengaged to return the bar N<3> by a projection q on a spring-held lever Q. The bars H are raised to the operative position again by pins R projecting laterally from two bars R', vertically movable by means of two bell-cranks and a longitudinally sliding rod S<1> operated by suitable means, shown in Fig. 1. In order to stop the apparatus, preferably in the mid-stroke of the cross-head D', an adjustable stop P, Fig. 2, secured to the bar N<3> engages a projection P' on a lever P<2>, pivoted to a stud p on the carriage I. The lever P<2> is thus lifted and the end p<1> of the projection P' intercepts the cross-head D<3> when the crosshead is moving towards the left, whereby the lever P<2> is carried along until its end p<3> abuts against the stop p<4>, taking with it the carriage I. In this position the rod i<1> moves the clutch C into mid-position, thus stopping the apparatus. In order to permit movement of the cylinder A without disturbing the controlling- mechanism, the bevel-gear E<1> is connected to its shaft E<2> by a clutch E<x>.

column12: Improvements in or relating to pipeline pigging

column13: The invention relates to a method and apparatus for laying pipeline from a vessel V. The vessel V has pipelaying equipment including apparatus for fabricating pipeline P along a fabrication axis (the fabrication axis being closer to horizontal than vertical), a stinger 12 pivotable between a deployed configuration and a retracted configuration (the stinger 12 supporting the fabricated pipeline P in an arcuate path between the fabrication axis and a departure axis which is aligned with pipeline suspended beneath the vessel), and a tower 10 pivotable between a lowered configuration and an elevated configuration (the tower 10 lying substantially parallel with the fabrication axis in the lowered configuration and being substantially aligned with the departure axis in the elevated configuration). The method includes a) pivoting the stinger 12 away from the deployed configuration and into the retracted configuration when it is desired to attach a module to the pipeline P, b) before or after step a) attaching a module to the pipeline P, c) lowering the section of pipeline P from the tower 10 along the departure axis until the attached module is below the retracted stinger 12, and d) pivoting the stinger 12 away from the retracted configuration and into the deployed configuration to allow continued laying of fabricated pipeline P.

A removable screen arrangement for a dishwasher having a washing chamber closed at its lower end by a sump (10) with a floor (18). The screen arrangement comprises a hollow enclosure (11) mounted low in the sump supported by a short pipe (20) connected at its lower end (22) to a circulation pump. The hollow enclosure is finely perforated over at least the major portion of its downwardly facing wall (14). Washing water during the dish washing cycle is drawn upwardly from below the hollow enclosure through the screen and thence to the pump inlet. The assembly is a push-on, pull-off sliding fit on the top of pipe (20), mating via a spigot (19). Thus the screen arrangement may be readily removed for cleaning but at all times during use the filtered food particles on the screen are not visible inside the washing chamber.

column12: Cell-based therapy for the pulmonary system
column13: Cell based therapy comprises administration to the lung by injection into the blood system of viable, mammalian cells effective for alleviating or inhibiting pulmonary disorders. The cells may express a therapeutic transgene or the cells may be therapeutic in their own right by inducing regenerative effects.

column13: A cooking appliance includes a vessel to receive liquid to be heated, a heater associated with the vessel to heat the liquid, a perforated basket for receiving food to be cooked by immersion in the liquid, and drive motor and threaded shaft for lowering and raising the basket into and out of the liquid as desired. The appliance is particularly suitable for cooking pasta or deep-frying chips.

column12: Fremgangsmåte og anordning for installasjon av en fôring i en rörledning
column13: System for å transportere en plugg (28) langs det indre av en rørledning (26) , spesielt for det formål å installere en foring (12) i rørledningen ved å trekke foringen bak pluggen, hvori det tilveiebringes en vannsøyle på hver side av pluggen og vannsøylen på pluggens nedstrømsside reduseres, slik at pluggen transporteres langs det indre av rørled-ningen ved hjelp av den resulterende trykkdifferanse. Når systemet anvendes i en på forhånd eksisterende undervannsrørledning, vil vannsøylene kunne tilveiebringes ved hjelp av stigerør (14, 24) og trykkdifferansen skapes ved hjelp av en pumpe (30) som er innrettet til å pumpe vann ut av nedstrømsstigerøret (24) . Fåringen vil kunne trekkes gjennom et vannfylt rør ved hjelp av en plugg, kabel, selvdreven rør-beltevogn, eller ved kombinasjoner av disse. En ytterligere kabel vil også kunne anvendes for å utøve bakoverrettet strekk og/eller for å begrense trekk-kraften som utøves på foringen og/eller for å gjøre det mulig å trekke fåringen bakover.

An electrical pressure sensing switch for a pressure cooker comprises a plunger slidably and sealingly mounted in a lid of a cooking vessel. The plunger is moved towards one end of a pivoted lever when pressure rises inside the vessel. The other end of the lever is positioned to press down against an operating arm. When the force applied by the plunger as a result of higher pressures in the vessel is sufficient to overcome bias of a spring , the arm is moved down by the lever. This results in operation of micro-switches Embodiments of the invention are mechanically simple and accommodate wide tolerances without loss of calibration, while necessary electrical parts are separated or separable from the lid to facilitate cleaning and washing.

A first adaptor 11 and a second adaptor 12 arrangement is provided wherein the provision of a coding lug (100B, Fig. 8B), together with sprung 21, 16, 17 and unsprung 14, 22 (23, Fig 5) electrical contacts, prevents accidental insertion of standard electrical equipment, such as normal dual contact lamps, into a live electricity supply. A cable has a plurality of first adaptors mounted along its lengths. Such cable may be mounted within a building or on a building site and lighting equipment may be installed as and when required. Because of the reciprocating nature of sprung and unsprung electrical contacts only specific equipment may be used in conjunction with the cable. <IMAGE>

column12: Dynamic clock feedback latching circuit and its latching method
column13: The invention relates to a dynamic clock feedback latching circuit and its latching method. The dynamic clock feedback latching circuit comprises a feedback path, when the clock input drops to the low level, a data value as the data input function is output; when the clock input rises to the high level and after a timing period, a preset latching value is generated. When the clock input is the low level, one node is precharged to the high logic value by a first transistor. When the clock input is the high level, a discharge path is provided by a second transistor for discharging the precharged high logic value of the node to the low logic value. In the timing period, the output of the feedback path controls a third transistor and when the data value is the high level, the node is discharged to the low logic value; when the data value is the low level, the node is kept at the precharged high logic value. When the clock output rises to the high level and after the timing period, the preset latching value is generated on the feedback path and the reverse phase value of the data value is latched on the node.

A convertible mat (10) is provided and comprises a generally planar base (20) and a border extending around the base, the border comprising border sections (25, 26, 27, 28) joined together by webs, the webs being single, substantially non-folding web sections (35, 36, 37, 38) which cause the border sections to be movable together between a first position in which they are coplanar with the base and a second position in which they are inclined whereby to form a tray.

column12: ROLL RETARDER IN PAPER DISPENSING DEVICE
Intermediate frequency slope compensation control arrangements.
column13: In a microwave digital radio transmission system receiver in which a modulated carrier wave is converted to an I.F. signal (1) which is demodulated (11-17) to produce phase quadrature signals (I, Q), an apparent frequency error of the carrier wave is detected from the phase quadrature signals (I, Q) and used to control an I.F. amplitude equalizer (2), for compensating for amplitude slope of the I.F. signal. A control signal is produced by low pass filtering (25) a product (22 or 23) of one phase quadrature signal (I or Q) with the time differential (20 or 21) of the other, or the difference (24) between the products of each phase quadrature signal with the time differential of the respective other phase quadrature signal.

column12: Improvements in Chimney and Ventilating Shaft Tops.
column13: 23,605. MacLeod, J. D. Nov. 4. Chimney and ventilating-shaft tops.-A single or double pyramid or cone, with one or more pyramidal or conical frusta arranged above it is supported within a chimney or ventilating-shaft top having lateral openings between louvers or concentric shafts so as to deflect down-draught into these openings. As shown in Fig. 9, a double cone d is supported within louvers above a contracted shaft a. The frusta e,f are such that the spaces between them taper downwards, and their lower and upper edges may lie in the continuations of the surfaces of the lower and upper cones respectively. Similar frusta may be employed within a concentric shaft surrounding the upper part of the contracted shaft of a top as shown in Fig. 5, or one frustum e only may be employed with its lower and upper edges on a level with the base and apex respectively of the upper cone as there shown. The edges of the frusta may take positions intermediate between those shown, and their surfaces are so sloped that they clear the upper edge of the lowest portion of the pot by a minimum of 22¢ degrees. The cone and frusta may be removable to facilitate cleaning.

column12: IMPROVEMENTS RELATING TO ABANDONMENT AND RECOVERY OF PIPELINES
column13: A method of abandoning a pipeline during subsea pipelaying from a pipelay vessel (28) comprises suspending the pipe string (38) from a tendon element (36) of an abandonment string and engaging further tendon elements (36) to an upper end of the abandonment string while lowering the pipe string (38) to a handover depth. At the handover depth, tension is applied via a wire (48) to the top of the pipe string (38) at an acute angle to the launch axis. This deflects the pipe string (38) from the launch axis into axial alignment with the wire (48) to transfer the weight load of the pipe string (38) to the wire (48), whereupon the abandonment string can be decoupled from the pipe string (38). Recovery of the pipeline from the seabed can be effected by a reverse process.

column12: Welding a metallically sheathed heating element to a metal vessel
column13: A method of welding a heating element having a metal sheath 11 to a metal vessel 12, e.g. a kettle, by heating the vessel 12 to a temperature close to its melting point, holding the element against a surface of the vessel 12, passing an electric current through the conductor part of the element 10 to raise the temperature of the sheath 11 and the contacted surface 13 of the vessel 12 to a temperature at which the contacting surfaces fuse and weld together. Preferably the heating element is welded to the outside of the vessel 12 and it is the inside of the vessel 12 that is heated, by for example an induction heater 14.

column12: Improvements in Horse and like Velocipedes for Children.
PIPE SUPPORT SYSTEM WITH MULTIPLE CLAMPS
column13: The present invention relates to an apparatus for and a method of holding high top tension pipeline (101) during pipe-lay from a rolling and pitching vessel (730). In one implementation, a clamp system (711, 712) for supporting a pipe on a vessel includes a first clamp for coupling to the pipe and a second clamp for coupling to the pipe. The second clamp is disposed above the first clamp. At least one of the first clamp or the second clamp is movable relative to the other of the first clamp or the second clamp.

An elongate sling section is disclosed. The elongate sling is cooperable with like sling sections to form a sling for use in abandonment or recovery of a pipeline. The sling section includes end-pieces at five opposite ends and complementary connector formations associated with each respective end-piece. Each connector formation is cooperable, in use when forming a sling, with a complementary connector formation of a neighbouring sling section in the sling. The sling section further includes a tensile load-bearing sling element extending between the end-pieces and a sleeve around the sling element.

column12: HYSTERESIS BRAKE AND METHOD OF CALIBRATION THEREOF
column13: HYSTERESIS BRAKE AND METHOD OF CALIBRATION THEREOF A hysteresis brake including a casing having internal alternating first slots and first teeth, a pole having external alternating second slots and second teeth, a rotor including an annular portion located in spaced relationship between the casing and pole, and structure for permitting the pole and casing to be rotationally adjusted relative to each other and to lock the first slots and teeth of the casing in a rotationally adjusted position relative to the second slots and teeth of the pole to cause the brake to provide a torque output of a substantially predetermined value at a predetermined current. A method of calibrating a hysteresis brake to provide a torque of a substantially predetermined value at a predetermined current including the steps of rotating the casing and pole relative to each other to a position which provides substantially the desired torque at the predetermined current, and locking the casing and pole to each other in that position.

column13: This hysteresis type magnetic device has a permanent magnet secured between two magnetizable pole members on a sleeve which is rotatably mounted on the output shaft coaxially thereof. One pole member is disposed within the other and has a plurality of axially extending external teeth or poles which confront but are radially spaced from a like plurality of internal teeth or poles on the outer pole member. A magnetizable, cup-shaped rotor is secured to the output shaft and has its annular wall projecting into the radial space between the inner and outer poles. The outer pole member is angularly adjustable relative to the inner to vary the angular separation between inner and outer poles, respectively, and hence to vary the transmittable torque in continuous slip braking and continuous or zero slip clutching connections.

An improved metallic cooking utensil suitable for use both in stovetop cooking such as frying and in a microwave oven is disclosed. The utensil features a bowl member formed of a single piece of stainless steel having a relatively square cut-off edge, that is, without a rolled-over edge or other complex edge detail. The upper portion of the disk member forms a circumferential flange which is extended at least two points to receive handles. The handles are formed of a microwave-transparent polymer material, and are affixed to the extended portions of the flange by rivets extending through square holes formed in the flange extensions. The bowl defines a relatively broad radius between its bottom portion and the upper flange, and may have a heat conductive element plated onto or affixed to its bottom for improvement of its heat conducting characteristics.

column12: Bidirectional telemetry apparatus and methods for wellbore operations

column13: Embodiments provide methods and systems for modeling a proposed geological volume. One such embodiment begins by digitally creating a three-dimensional (3D) model of a geological volume that includes one or more variables, each of which is a mathematical factor in an analysis confidence of one or more sub-volumes of the volume. Next, standardized values for each of the one or more variables are defined. In turn, the analysis confidence, e.g. mined, ore quality, etc., of the one or more sub-volumes is mathematically determined. Finally, the model is updated to include the determined analysis confidence of the one or more sub-volumes.

1,181,442. Textile treating compositions. GAF CORP. 18 May, 1967 [20 May, 1966], No. 23058/67. Heading C3R. [Also in Division D1] An aqueous textile finish composition comprises (a) 0À2-5 p.b.w. of a hydrolysed vinyl ether-maleic anhydride copolymer, (b) 1-20 parts by weight of a thermosetting melamine resin, (c) 0À2-5 parts of an acidic catalyst, and optionally (d) up to 8 parts of an acrylic latex, (e) up to 0À5 parts of ammonium zirconyl carbonate, and (f) up to 10 parts of an anionic or non- ionic fabric softener, the remainder to 100 parts being water. The copolymer (a) may be hydrolysed methyl vinyl ether/maleic anhydride; the resin (b) may be an alkylated or unmodified methylol melamine; the catalyst (c) may be 2-amino-2-methyl-1-propanol hydrochloride or phosphate, ethanolamine hydrochloride, 2- amino-1-butanol phosphate, triethanolamine phosphate, diethanolamine hydrochloride, 3- amino - 2 - methyl - 2 - butanol hydrochloride, diammonium phosphate, MgCl 2 , ZnCl 2 , NH 4 Cl, Zn(NO 3 ) 2 , oxalic acid or citric acid. The latex (d) may be of a polymer of acrylic or methacrylic methyl, ethyl or propyl ester or amide; the softener (f) may he, e.g., a long-chain alkyl carboxylic, sulphonic or sulphuric acid salt, a polyoxyethylenated long-chain active hydrogen compound, and fatty acid esters and amides. In Examples aqueous solutions are prepared containing by weight 1À5-3% of a hydrolysed poly(vinyl methyl ether-maleic anhydride) and 2À5-8% of polymethylol melamine; and optionally 0À5-1À4% of Zn(NO 3 ) 2 or 0À5% of NH 4 Cl or 0À8-1À4% of a hydroxy-amine hydrochloride; 1-2% of a fatty acid ethoxylate; 0À3% of ammonium zirconyl carbonate; 2-3% of an acrylic latex and 0À1% of oxalic acid.

column12: Cell-based therapy for the pulmonary system
column13: Cell based therapy comprises administration to the lung by injection into the blood system of viable, mammalian cells effective for alleviating or inhibiting pulmonary disorders. The cells may express a therapeutic transgene or the cells may be therapeutic in their own right by inducing regenerative effects.

column12: Improvements relating to abandonment and recovery of pipelines
column13: A method of abandoning a pipeline during subsea pipelaying from a pipelay vessel includes suspending the pipe string from a tendon element of an abandonment string and engaging further tendon elements to an upper end of the abandonment string while lowering the pipe string to a handover depth. At the handover depth, tension is applied via a wire to the top of the pipe string at an acute angle to the launch axis. This deflects the pipe string from the launch axis into axial alignment with the wire to transfer the weight load of the pipe string to the wire, whereupon the abandonment string can be decoupled from the pipe string. Recovery of the pipeline from the seabed can be effected by a reverse process.

column12: COMMUNICATION DEVICE HAVING A WIDEBAND RECEIVER AND OPERATING METHOD THEREFOR
column13: To accommodate for a release of uncleared spectrum in a wideband communication system (10) while improving isolation in a receiver (FIG. 4) between wideband carriers, a common intermediate frequency converter down-converts differing but relatively high frequency carriers, incident to the receiver, to corresponding differing but relatively low frequency carriers. Receiver chains (174-176) response to the plurality of relatively low frequency carriers each have a filter (140-144) arranged to isolate selected ones of the relatively low frequency carriers. In a radio frequency communication system having three or more frequency sequential carriers, the receiver chains (174-176) may include branches that have filters that further isolate carriers within the receiver by applying non-sequential carriers to the branches in each receiver chain.

A welding operation is initiated by closure of switch 3a which applies the voltage from the rectifier 2 (70 volts) to the electrode 4 by way of a spark generator 6 which produces trains of trigger pulses. An arc between the electrode 4 and workpiece 5 is then produced by changeover of the switch 12 from the position shown whereby the capacitor voltage (300 volts) is superimposed upon that of the rectifier 2 whereupon the main welding burner is supplied from rectifier 2 until terminated by opening switch 3a. The workpiece 5 may be stainless steel in a helium atmosphere.

column13: Means for securing a polymer liner to the inner surface of a pipe comprises an end piece consisting of a hub portion and a corrosion resistant metallic insert. The polymer hub is fusion welded to the end of the liner, and the metallic insert is seal welded portion of the inner surface of the pipe clad with corrosion resistant material at a distance from the outer end of the pipe. The clad portion may be provided by a pup piece welded to the end of the pipe. This arrangement allows two lengths of lined pipes to be joined by welding with a continuous corrosion resistant internal surface, without damage to the polymer pipe linings and in a manner which allows an assembled pipe string to be spooled onto a reel for subsequent pipelaying operations. In the preferred embodiment, the metal insert is screw-threaded to the polymer hub with an elastomeric seal therebetween, which provides a secondary seal between the end piece and the pipe wall. An alternative means of terminating a polymer lining sleeve for other purposes, such as a flange-type joint, is also disclosed.

An improved metallic cooking utensil suitable for use both in stovetop cooking such as frying and in a microwave oven is disclosed. The utensil features a bowl member (10) formed of a single piece of stainless steel having a relatively square cut-off edge, that is, without a rolled-over edge or other complex edge detail. The upper portion of the dish member forms a circumferential flange which is extended at least two points (18, 20) to receive handles. The handles are formed of a microwave-transparent polymer material, and are affixed to the extended portions (18, 20) of the flange by rivets extending through square holes formed in the flange extensions (18, 20). The bowl (10) defines a relatively broad radius between its bottom portion (12) and the upper flange, and may have a heat conductive element (11, 30) plated onto or affixed to its bottom for improvement of its heat conducting characteristics.

A vacuum coffee maker has a starved electric heating arrangement 13 having a solid body 16 providing a reservoir 17. The chamber is covered by a circular lid 19 that prevents flow of steam directly vertically up a tube 12 from the chamber 17. At the end of a normal heating cycle, the temperature of the body 16 rises rapidly and power supplied to a heating element 18 is automatically turned off under the control of a thermostat 25. The heating arrangement 13 is used without alteration (e.g. to the setting of the thermostat) to keep-warm hot coffee in a lower container 11 after the end of the normal heating coffee-making cycle. The effect of having the lid 19 is that during a keep-warm function, the reservoir is generally starved of liquid because any liquid entering the reservoir is immediately evaporated and this restricts flow of more liquid into the reservoir and hence starves the reservoir.

10,078. McRae, J. D. May 1. Centrifugal pumps.-Relates to a condensing system suitable for places where economy in the use of water is necessary, rendering it desirable to use the water over and over again continuously, and one of the chief objects is to arrange so that all the requisite pumping is performed by a single pump. Fig. 7 shows in diagrammatic form an example of the apparatus complete. In this, a denotes a cooling-tower or other cooling-device, b the condenser supplied with condensing water by the injection pipe 2, 1 the pipe delivering steam to be condensed into the condenser, and c the combined air and circulating pump by which air, vapour, and water are withdrawn from the condenser, and the whole body of water is kept circulating through the pipes 4, 5 and the cooler a. Fig. 1 shows in section one form of jet condenser and pump, and Fig. 3 shows the pump in section. The pump is a double centrifugal pump with a set of blades f<1> for drawing from the suction chamber k which communicates with the pipe 5, and a set of vertical tubes i for drawing from a central cavity f<2> in the boss f which communicates with the condenser b. Each of the tubes i is formed with a contracted portion i<1> designed to facilitate the flow of water through them. The pump casing consists of two heads j', j' and a peripheral ring j forming the discharge chamber and connected with the pipe 4. The pump casing is connected with the condenser by aT-pipe h forming a stuffing-box surrounding an extension g of the boss f. The packing is adjusted by a sliding sleeve or gland h<4> prevented from rotating by a pin and adjusted by a central screw h'. In place of a jet condenser, an induction condenser may be employed, as shown in Fig. 8. In this, the steam to be condensed enters at 1 and the condensing water at 2, and the pump is constructed to draw from only one source. A similar pump drawing from two sources on one side is also shown.

column12: IMPROVED INDUCTION HEATING APPARATUS AND METHOD FOR PIPELINE WELDING OPERATIONS
column13: Induction heating apparatus for use in welding an end of a first length of pipe (26) to the exterior surface of a second length of pipe (28), consists of heating assemblies (20, 24) each comprising at least one electrical induction coil (32, 36) wound on an annular, laminated, magnetic core assembly (30, 34). The lowermost surfaces of said core assembly (30, 34) define a saddle shape adapted to be seated on the exterior surface of said second length of pipe (28). The arrangement of the coils (32, 36) and the core assemblies (30, 34) is such that substantially all of the magnetic flux generated when the apparatus is seated on the pipe (28) and the coil is energised is contained within the core assembly and within the wall of the pipe (28). Advantageously, the core assemblies (30, 34) have E-sections profiles, the ends of the limbs of the E-sections comprising the lowermost surfaces of the core assemblies and the coils being wound about the central limbs of the E-sections. The core assembly is formed from a plurality of part-annular segments, each segment having an individual induction coil associated therewith. The apparatus may comprise first and second heating assemblies, the first extending around the outer periphery of a circular weld zone defined on the exterior surface of said second length of pipe and the second extending around the inner periphery of the weld zone.

column12: Bucket converter for an excavation bucket
column13: A bucket converter for providing improved excavation versatility that couples with and attaches to an excavation. The bucket converter comprises a volume increasing frame coupled and semi-fixedly attached to an excavation bucket for increasing the volumetric capacity of the excavation bucket. An orienting projection from a lower portion of the frame holds the coupling element of the frame at a height above a surface when the bucket converter is detached from the excavation bucket and is supported on the surface by the orienting projection and a lowermost portion of the frame. The height at which the coupling portion is held by the orienting projection enables engagement of the coupling portion with a cooperative coupling element on the excavation bucket without the need for any initial manual assistance. Additionally, the bucket converter also provides additional functionality to an excavation bucket by providing an alternative cutting edge to the excavation bucket to which it is attached, thereby eliminating the need for multiple buckets at an excavation site.

column12: DISTORTION COMPENSATION CONTROL FOR A POWER AMPLIFIER
column13: A control arrangement and method for controlling a gain and phase adjuster used for controlling the gain and phase of a compensation signal for compensating for the distortion produced by a power amplifier is disclosed. The control arrangement makes use of a reference signal, of known frequency, which is amplified along with the desired carrier signals. The reference signal component of the amplified signal is then isolated and a comparison is made, either with the actual reference signal, e.g., by a QAM demodulator, or alternatively with the known frequency of the reference signal, e.g., by a FM discriminator, in order to determine the differences in gain and in phase of the reference signal component of the amplified signal in comparison with the reference signal. For example, a QAM demodulator is used for producing a first difference signal indicative of the phase switch difference, and a second difference signal indicative of the gain switch difference. These signals are then correlated with the signal envelope of the main signal in order to produce signals indicative of the sign and magnitude of the control signals used to adjust the gain and phase adjuster in a feed back loop.

column12: APPARATUS AND METHOD OF LAYING PIPELINE
column13: The invention relates to a method and apparatus for laying pipeline (8) from a vessel (V). The vessel (V) has pipelaying equipment including apparatus for fabricating pipeline along a fabrication axis (the fabrication axis being closer to horizontal than vertical), a stinger (12) pivotable between a deployed configuration and a retracted configuration (the stinger (12) supporting the fabricated pipeline (P) in an arcuate path between the fabrication axis and a departure axis which is aligned with pipeline suspended beneath the vessel), and a tower (10) pivotable between a lowered configuration and an elevated configuration (the tower lying substantially parallel with the fabrication axis in the lowered configuration and being substantially aligned with the departure axis in the elevated configuration). The method includes a) pivoting the stinger away from the deployed configuration and into the retracted configuration when it is desired to attach a module to the pipeline, b) before or after step a) attaching a module to the pipeline, c) lowering the section of pipeline from the tower along the departure axis until the attached module is below the retracted stinger, and d) pivoting the stinger away from the retracted configuration and into the deployed configuration to allow continued laying of fabricated pipeline.

column13: Means for securing a polymer pipe liner (14, 16) to the inner surface of a pipe comprises an end piece (100, 101) consisting of a hub portion (102) and a corrosion resistant metallic insert (104). The polymer hub is fusion welded to the end of the liner, and the metallic insert is seal welded portion of the inner surface of the pipe clad with corrosion resistant material (22) at a distance from the outer end of the pipe. The clad portion may be provided by a pup piece (18, 20) welded to the end of the pipe. This arrangement allows two lengths of lined pipes to be joined by welding with a continuous corrosion resistant internal surface, without damage to the polymer pipe linings and in a manner which allows an assembled pipe string to be spooled onto a reel for subsequent pipelaying operations. In the preferred embodiment, the metal insert is screw-threaded to the polymer hub with an elastomeric seal (110) therebetween, which provides a secondary seal between the end piece and the pipe wall. An alternative means of terminating a polymer lining sleeve for other purposes, such as a flange-type pipe joint, is also disclosed.

Improvements relating to abandonment and recovery of pipelines
column13: A method of abandoning a pipeline during subsea pipelaying from a pipelay vessel (28) comprises suspending the pipe string (38) from a tendon element (36) of an abandonment string and engaging further tendon elements (36) to an upper end of the abandonment string while lowering the pipe string (38) to a handover depth. At the handover depth, tension is applied via a wire (48) to the top of the pipe string (38) at an acute angle to the launch axis. This deflects the pipe string (38) from the launch axis into axial alignment with the wire (48) to transfer the weight load of the pipe string (38) to the wire (48), whereupon the abandonment string can be decoupled from the pipe string (38). Recovery of the pipeline from the seabed can be effected by a reverse process.

column12: Dynamic clock feedback latching circuit and its latching method
column13: The invention relates to a dynamic clock feedback latching circuit and its latching method. The dynamic clock feedback latching circuit comprises a feedback path, when the clock input drops to the low level, a data value as the data input function is output; when the clock input rises to the high level and after a timing period, a preset latching value is generated. When the clock input is the low level, one node is precharged to the high logic value by a first transistor. When the clock input is the high level, a discharge path is provided by a second transistor for discharging the precharged high logic value of the node to the low logic value. In the timing period, the output of the feedback path controls a third transistor and when the data value is the high level, the node is discharged to the low logic value; when the data value is the low level, the node is kept at the precharged high logic value. When the clock output rises to the high level and after the timing period, the preset latching value is generated on the feedback path and the reverse phase value of the data value is latched on the node.

column12: Improvements relating to abandonment and recovery of pipelines
column13: A method of abandoning a pipeline during subsea pipelaying comprises suspending the pipe string from a tendon element of an abandonment string and engaging further tendon elements to an upper end of the abandonment string while lowering the pipe string to a handover depth. A tendon element comprises a tensile load-bearing member extending between end connector formations and at least one sleeve removably mounted around the load bearing member. At the handover depth, tension is applied via a wire to the top of the pipe string at an acute angle to the launch axis. This deflects the pipe string from the launch axis into axial alignment with the wire to transfer the weight load of the pipe string to the wire, whereupon the abandonment string can be decoupled from the pipe string. Recovery of the pipeline from the seabed can be effected by a reverse process.

The output controls a third transistor during the delay to drain the node to a low value if the data value is high and to retain the high value if the data value is low. column13: A gas water heating system is described that utilises most of the heat of combustion of the fuel in an area remote from the tank itself. column12: DISTORTION COMPENSATION CONTROL FOR A POWER AMPLIFIER
column13: A control arrangement and method for controlling a gain and phase adjuster used for controlling the gain and phase of a compensation signal for compensating for the distortion produced by a power amplifier is disclosed. The control arrangement makes use of a reference signal, of known frequency, which is amplified along with the desired carrier signals. The reference signal component of the amplified signal is then isolated and a comparison is made, either with the actual reference signal, e.g., by a QAM demodulator, or alternatively with the known frequency of the reference signal, e.g., by a FM discriminator, in order to determine the differences in gain and in phase of the reference signal component of the amplified signal in comparison with the reference signal. For example, a QAM demodulator is used for producing a first difference signal indicative of the phase switch difference, and a second difference signal indicative of the gain switch difference. These signals are then correlated with the signal envelope of the main signal in order to produce signals indicative of the sign and magnitude of the control signals used to adjust the gain and phase adjuster in a feed back loop.

column13: Induction heating apparatus for use in welding an end of a first length of pipe (26) to the exterior surface of a second length of pipe (28), consists of heating assemblies (20, 24) each comprising at least one electrical induction coil (32, 36) wound on an annular, laminated, magnetic core assembly (30, 34). The lowermost surfaces of said core assembl y (30, 34) define a saddle shape adapted to be seated on the exterior surface of said second length of pipe (28). The arrangement of the coils (32, 36) and the core assemblies (30, 34) is such that substantially all of the magnetic flux generated when the apparatus is seate d on the pipe (28) and the coil is energised is contained within the core assembly and within the wall of the pipe (28). Advantageously, the core assemblies (30, 34) have E-sections profiles, the ends of the limbs of the E-sections comprising the lowermost surfaces of the core assemblies and the coils being wound about the central limbs of the E-sections. The core assembly is formed from a plurality of part-annular segments, each segment having an individual induction coil associated therewith. The apparatus may comprise first and second heating assemblies, the first extending around the outer periphery of a circular weld zone defined on the exterior surface of said second length of pipe and the second extending around the inner periphery of the weld zone.

column12: Improvements in or relating to fluid pipelines
column13: Means for securing a polymer pipe liner (14, 16) to the inner surface of a pipe comprises an end piece (100, 101) consisting of a hub portion (102) and a corrosion resistant metallic insert (104). The polymer hub is fusion welded to the end of the liner, and the metallic insert is seal welded portion of the inner surface of the pipe clad with corrosion resistant material (22) at a distance from the outer end of the pipe. The clad portion may be provided by a pup piece (18, 20) welded to the end of the pipe. This arrangement allows two lengths of lined pipes to be joined by welding with a continuous corrosion resistant internal surface, without damage to the polymer pipe linings and in a manner which allows an assembled pipe string to be spooled onto a reel for subsequent pipelaying operations. In the preferred embodiment, the metal insert is screw-threaded to the polymer hub with an elastomeric seal (110) therebetween, which provides a secondary seal between the end piece and the pipe wall. An alternative means of terminating a polymer lining sleeve for other purposes, such as a flange-type pipe joint, is also disclosed.
