column13: L'invention se rapporte à un dispositif distributeur (10) servant à distribuer un agent de nettoyage ou un concentré de détergent liquide dans une zone de lavage d'une machine à laver durant une phase d'un cycle de lavage. La machine à laver comprend une pompe à eau (10) qui assure les fonctions normales associées aux cycles de lavage. La pression de l'eau provenant de la pompe est utilisée pour ejecter ou faire sortir par pression une quantité prédéterminée du concentré d'un récipient (28) jusque dans la zone de lavage à une phase désirée du processus de lavage. Dans un mode de réalisation, le récipient pour le concentré se présente sous la forme d'un sachet flexible (28) comportant un bec de sortie (32) scellé jusqu'à ce qu'il soit placé pour la première fois dans un logement (11) en vue de son utilisation. Pendant l'utilisation, le bec (32) fait saillie à travers une ouverture ménagée dans une fermeture (12) du logement et débouche dans la zone de lavage. Via une seconde ouverture ménagée dans le logement, un petit volume d'eau sous pression provenant de la pompe est dirigé sous la commande synchronisée d'un clapet (26) à la phase requise du cycle de lavage jusque dans le logement fermé. Le logement peut être divisé en compartiments et un orifice de communication (20) sépare un compartiment (16) d'un autre (18), de façon à ce que le sachet se trouvant dans le compartiment (16) soit soumis au contact de l'eau chaude provenant de la pompe pendant un minimum de temps seulement.

column13: A gas water heating system is described that utilises most of the heat of combustion of the fuel in an area remote from the tank itself. It also provides a cold lower tank area that stays cooler than the bulk of the volume of the tank through the heating cycle. It also provides a cold lower tank area above the flue outlet of the remote heat exchanger further enhancing the efficiency. It also delivers hotter water to the top of the tank, thereby filling the tank with hot water from the top down. It also utilises the superior insulating properties of plastic foam. It also efficiently uses the pilot flame heat without it causing a high airflow through the unit, with attendant thermal losses. The tank unit is easily replaced in the event of a tank leak or rupture, but retaining the gas equipment and heat exchanger for further use. The central flue has been deleted, and the products of combustion are now directed up the outside of the tank surface in a gap provided between the tank outer wall and a metal sheet wrap to keep the hot gases against the tank wall. Two or more separate fluid paths that are in good mutual contact for efficient heat transfer. The fluid paths are generally tubular and the length of the tubing on one side of the heat exchanger carrying a first fluid may be shorter or longer than that for the second fluid. iPi2 11

column12: System and Method for Monitoring Electrolyte Levels in a Battery
column13: A measuring device is used in conjunction with a programmable controller for monitoring electrolyte levels in the battery. According to one implementation, the measuring device is located in a battery and is configured to detect when the electrolyte level in the battery falls below a particular level. The controller is in electrical communication with the electrolyte detection device. The controller is configured to: (i) receive a signal from the electrolyte level detection device indicating when the electrolyte level in the battery has fallen below the particular level; (ii) introduce a wait-period after the signal is received; and (iii) enable an indicator to indicate that the electrolyte level in the battery should be refilled when the wait-period expires.

column12: System and method for determining characteristics of a plurality of people at an event based on mobile phone tracking and mobile data transmission
column13: Technologies are described herein for determining characteristics of a plurality of people at an event. A method may include receiving location information about a plurality of active mobile phones, receiving sentiment information relating to the plurality of people, the sentiment information including at least one identifier of the event, determining at least one characteristic about the plurality of people based at least in part on the location information and the sentiment information, aggregating the sentiment information, classifying the aggregated sentiment information as either favorable or unfavorable with respect to the event, and calculating a statistical confidence level indicating an extent the aggregated sentiment information of the particular group correlates with the plurality of people. The location information may include at least one identifier of a geographical location and a time period. The location information and sentiment information may be collected from a particular group of the plurality of people.

column12: Internet based method and system for ranking individuals using a popularity profile
column13: Technologies are described herein for determining popularity of an individual. A popularity profiling server is used to receive information of the individual, analyze a quantitative data portion of the information, and analyze a qualitative data portion of the information using sentiment analysis. The sentiment analysis uses natural language parsing to separate the qualitative data into parts of speech. The popularity profiling server calculates an initial set of scores for the popularity of the individual based on the analysis of the quantitative data portion and the qualitative data portion of the information, update a ranking for the popularity of the individual in a database, and determine, after waiting a predetermined amount of time, if new data has been updated to the information on the information server. If new information has been updated, an updated set of scores are calculated.

column12: System and method for monitoring electrolyte levels in a battery
column13: A measuring device (128) is used in conjunction with a programmable controller for monitoring electrolyte levels in the battery. According to one implementation, the measuring device is located in a battery and is configured to detect when the electrolyte level in the battery falls below the electrolyte detection device. The controller (132) is operable in one of a selectable test mode or non-test mode, wherein when the test mode is selected the controller (132) enables the measuring device (128) to be energized for sensing whether the electrolyte level in the battery (102) is above or below the electrolyte detection device, and wherein when the non-test mode is selected the controller (132) enables the measuring device (128) to be de-energized. The controller (132) is in electrical communication with the probe (134). The invention also relates to a power management system for managing current usage of a probe (134) used for sensing the electrolyte level in a battery (102).

Chariot à provisions à roues muni de moyens pour le transport d'un bébé et de préférence aussi d'un petit enfant.

Il comprend un panier à provisions 3 pour le transport de marchandises achetées, un berceau à bébé 4 situé en bas et muni d'une courroie de sécurité 7, un siège pour enfant 8 situé plus haut que le berceau 4 et aussi muni d'une courroie de sécurité 9, tant le berceau que le siège étant orientés, de sorte que le bébé soit étendu et l'enfant, assis transversalement à la direction de poussée normale. En vue de la stabilité, tant le berceau 4 que le siège 8 sont situés au-dessus de la zone délimitée par les roues du chariot. Un couvercle 6 est affecté au berceau 4 pour éviter au bébé d'être blessé par des articles tombant. Deux poignées latérales 5 sont prévues pour permettre de faire franchir au chariot une voie d'accès à une caisse en le poussant perpendiculairement à sa direction de poussée normale.

An exercise device providing a fore and aft horizontal component of striding motion that is dynamically user-defined, while providing a vertical component of the motion that is maintained on a predetermined vertically reciprocating path in some embodiments. The exercise device guides the user's foot in a pseudo-elliptical stride path, while providing a dynamically variable stride length that allows the user to move with a natural stride length. The exercise device allows tall and short users to extend or curtail the stride length to match their natural stride lengths. The length of the reciprocating path is dynamically adjusted during the exercise operation without equipment adjustments by changes in the length of the stride input by the user at a pair of foot engagement pads disposed on laterally spaced apart foot support members.

A light source comprises a gas-tight container 1, Fig. 1, a #-radioactive gas within the container and a coating of phosphorescent material 3 on a major portion of the internal surface of the container, the container being light transparent at least over the remainder 6 of the surface, the arrangement being such as to concentrate the emitted light. The coating 3 is of sufficient thickness to absorb substantially a11 the #-radiation incident from the gas on to the coating. A device for use in combination with a pile driving apparatus for driving piles into the ground. The device (1) including a main body (13) which carries side grippers (18) and (19) each of which comprises a ram consisting of a piston and cylinder (20). A further gripper (23) is included, which extends downwardly of the main body (13) which grips the lower end of a pile, while grippers (18) and (19) are used to pick up and position a pile. System and Method for Monitoring Electrolyte Levels in a Battery
column13: A measuring device is used in conjunction with a programmable controller for monitoring electrolyte levels in the battery. According to one implementation, the measuring device is located in a battery and is configured to detect when the electrolyte level in the battery falls below a particular level. The controller is in electrical communication with the electrolyte detection device. The controller is configured to: (i) receive a signal from the electrolyte level detection device indicating when the electrolyte level in the battery has fallen below the particular level; (ii) introduce a wait-period after the signal is received; and (iii) enable an indicator to indicate that the electrolyte level in the battery should be refilled when the wait-period expires.

column13: 1,210,124. Jointing by stamping; making electrical connections; punching. CCL SYSTEMS Ltd. 31 Jan., 1969 [14 Feb., 1968], No. 7249/68. Heading B3A, B3Q and B3W. Apparatus for attaching a metal fitting to an electrical conductor or other cable comprises three spaced indenting or piercing elements 21, 27, power-operated means 17 for moving the element 21, and further power-operated means 18 for moving the other elements 27. As shown, the apparatus has two pivoted crimping jaws 27, Fig. 2, and a central jaw 21 which is operated, against a return spring 20, by a piston 17. The pivoted jaws 27 are operated by pistons 18 and returned by springs 24. A cam 31, operated by a screw 28 and engaging followers 33 mounted on the jaws 27, may close the jaws 27 ahead of the pistons 18 to hold a fitting before crimping. The apparatus may have an insulating cover 34, and an hydraulic circuit for supplying the pistons may include a pressure relief valve. In a modification, Fig. 6, a single piston 41 operates both pivoted jaws 46 through toggle links 47. The piston 41 may be moved to obtain an initial grip by turning a knurled nut 50 engaging the screw-threaded pistonrod 49.

column12: DEVICE AND METHOD FOR MONITORING LIFE HISTORY AND CONTROLLING MAINTENANCE OF INDUSTRIAL BATTERIES
column13: This invention is a method and device for monitoring and storing data regarding the 'life history' of a battery with which it is associated and interpreting the data to create an accurate record of use and abuse patterns. A manufacturer's specified life expectancy, measured in battery cycles, is established for the battery under normal use, and then the actual use of the battery is monitored and stored. Complete cycles, partial cycles, and operation of the battery outside of acceptable specifications are automatically derived into a value in units equivalent to a number of battery cycles, and this derivation is compared with the manufacturers life expectancy, and adjustments to the manufacturers life expectancy are made so that a more accurate and up-to-date estimation of battery life can be evolved over the life of the battery. The monitoring device is mounted on the battery for the lifetime of the battery, with certain information regarding the battery being displayed to all persons having access to the battery. Additional information may be made available to an authorized person or entity. This enables a lessor of the battery, for example, to identify abuse of the battery by a lessee and adjust fees, lease terms, etc. accordingly.

column12: Internet based system and method for wagering on an artist
column13: Examples of systems and methods for wagering on an artist are disclosed. In one example according to aspects of the present disclosure, a computer implemented method for wagering on an artist includes: obtaining, by an electronic exchange of a wagering system server, an initial value for a metric related to the artist from a popularity profiling system server; receiving, by the electronic exchange, a transaction request from a client computer, wherein the transaction request relates to a wager on a future value of the metric related to the artist; generating, by the electronic exchange, a wager metric related to the transaction; and predicting, by a prediction engine of a wagering system server, the future value of the metric related to the artist based on the initial value of the metric and the wager metric.

INTERNET BASED METHOD AND SYSTEM FOR RANKING ARTISTS USING A POPULARITY PROFILE
column13: Technologies are described herein for determining popularity of an artist. A popularity profiling server is used to receive artist information, analyze a quantitative data portion of the artist information, and analyze a qualitative data portion of the artist information using sentiment analysis. The sentiment analysis uses natural language parsing to separate the qualitative data into parts of speech. The popularity profiling server calculates an initial set of scores for the popularity of the artist based on the analysis of the quantitative data portion and the qualitative data portion of the artist information, update a ranking for the popularity of the artist in a database, and determine, after waiting a predetermined amount of time, if new data has been updated to the artist information on the information server. If new artist information has been updated, an updated set of scores are calculated.

column12: System and method for determining audience characteristics of a music concert based on mobile phone tracking and mobile data transmissions
column13: A concert profiling server (CPS) obtains and analyzes information about a venue hosting a music concert and mobile phone location information related to the audience members attending the concert. Based on this information, the CPS determines the size of the audience in attendance. The CPS also obtains and analyzes sentiment information related to audience members at the concert with which the CPS determines the audience's sentiment toward the concert as favorable or unfavorable. The CPS further obtains and analyzes other information with which it makes a profile of the demographics of the audience and the audience members' levels of engagement.

column13: Examples of systems and methods for wagering on an individual are disclosed. In one example according to aspects of the present disclosure, a method for wagering on an individual includes: receiving, by a computer system, a plurality of metrics related to a popularity profile of the individual, wherein at least one metric of the plurality of metrics is based on sentiment analysis, determining, by the computer system, an initial value for each metric related to the popularity profile of the individual, generating, by the computer system, a wager metric of a particular metric related to the popularity profile of the individual based on a transaction request, and predicting, by the computer system, a future value of the particular metric based on the initial value of the particular metric and the wager metric.

column12: Device and method for monitoring life history and controlling maintenance of industrial batteries
column13: This invention is a method and device for monitoring and storing data regarding the “life history” of a battery with which it is associated and interpreting the data to create an accurate record of use and abuse patterns. A manufacturer's specified life expectancy, measured in battery cycles, is established for the battery under normal use, and then the actual use of the battery is monitored and stored. Complete cycles, partial cycles, and operation of the battery outside of acceptable specifications are automatically derived into a value in units equivalent to a number of battery cycles, and this derivation is compared with the manufacturers life expectancy, and adjustments to the manufacturers life expectancy are made so that a more accurate and up-to-date estimation of battery life can be evolved over the life of the battery. The monitoring device is mounted on the battery for the lifetime of the battery, with certain information regarding the battery being displayed to all persons having access to the battery. Additional information may be made available to an authorized person or entity. This enables a lessor of the battery, for example, to identify abuse of the battery by a lessee and adjust fees, lease terms, etc. accordingly.

column13: Described are improved transmissive magneto-optical sensors that may be used to determine the magnitude and phase of a magnetic field surrounding a conductor, and when in contact with the conductor, the surface temperature of the conductor. The magneto-optical sensor may be made to be symmetric around the direction of propagation of the internal light, enabling ease of manufacturing as well as automated assembly and calibration. The magneto-optical sensor may also be made to be symmetric about the plane determined by the Faraday rotator material (10), thus enabling reciprocating optical paths for increased vibration and birefringence immunity. The disclosed sensors preferably include cylindrically symmetrical components, thereby making the sensor readily mass-producible.

Precision approach path indicator using LEDs
column13: A Precision Approach Path Indicator (PAPI) unit (1 fig 2) comprises a light engine (30 fig 2) and a projection lens assembly 40. The light engine includes first and second light sources 366,367 that are red and white respectively and are mounted onto a PCB 361. Light emitted by the first and second light sources is collimated by lenses 362 and directed into first and second solid waveguides 37 and is guided by said waveguides to an intermediate plane. The waveguides are separated by a divider 365. The intermediate plane is located in a window 35 of a front plate 34 of the light engine. The intermediate plane also sits at the focal plane of the projection lens assembly 40. The arrangement enables the light emitted from LEDs to be focussed into properly directed beams which overcomes the problems with LEDs of their tendency to emit light over a large range of angles.

column13: A method and equipment for assessing the suitability of support surfaces such as mattresses and chairs is disclosed. column12: Device and method for monitoring life history and controlling maintenance of industrial batteries
column13: This invention is a method and device for monitoring and storing data regarding the "life history" of a battery with which it is associated and interpreting the data to create an accurate record of use and abuse patterns. A manufacturer's specified life expectancy, measured in battery cycles, is established for the battery under normal use, and then the actual use of the battery is monitored and stored. Complete cycles, partial cycles, and operation of the battery outside of acceptable specifications are automatically derived into a value in units equivalent to a number of battery cycles, and this derivation is compared with the manufacturers life expectancy, and adjustments to the manufacturers life expectancy are made so that a more accurate and up-to-date estimation of battery life can be evolved over the life of the battery. The monitoring device is mounted on the battery for the lifetime of the battery, with certain information regarding the battery being displayed to all persons having access to the battery. Additional information may be made available to an authorized person or entity. This enables a lessor of the battery, for example, to identify abuse of the battery by a lessee and adjust fees, lease terms, etc. accordingly.

column12: End-to-end voice over IP streams for telephone calls established via legacy switching systems
column13: When voice over Internet Protocol (IP) capabilities are added to a conventional network of voice switches, an IP network is normally used to replace individual trunks between voice switches and to replace telephone lines between telephones and their serving voice switches. As a result, calls across the upgraded network often pass across a series of IP hops. This invention addresses the problem of replacing a series of IP hops by a single hop, to avoid degradation of end-to-end voice quality due to repeated packetization/depacketization sequences and associated functions such as compression/decompression.

column12: METHOD OF MOLECULAR-SCALE PATTERN IMPRINTING AT SURFACES
column13: A method for mask-free molecular or atomic patterning of surfaces of reactive solids is disclosed. Molecules adsorb at surfaces in patterns, governed by the structure of the surface, the chemical nature of the adsorbate, and the adsorbate coverage at the surface. The surface is patterned and then imprinted with the pattern by inducing localized chemical reaction between adsorbate molecules and the surface of the solid, resulting in an imprint being formed in the vicinity of the adsorbate molecules. When the imprinted molecular patterns are conjugated chains containing π bonds along which electrical charge can flow the molecular patterns constitute molecular wires or the imprinted molecules constitute a molecular-scale device. The surface of the substrate can be doped by including n - or p- type dopants in the adsorbate molecules. These molecular wires are anchored to the substrate by using conjugated chains which can be chemically bound at intervals along the chains to the substrates.

column12: Determining User Availability Based on the Expected Duration of a New Event
column13: Techniques are disclosed for determining, for each candidate communication medium, the availability of one or more telecommunications endpoint users for participating in a communication session of interest (i.e., either new or existing) via the evaluated medium. In accordance with the illustrative embodiment of the present invention, an availability manager determines the availability based on (i) one or more discrete rules, or (ii) one or more continuous functions, or both. The continuous functions are specified with respect to the time that has elapsed since a previous session, the time remaining in an active session, and the expected duration of a new session. Once it has determined the availability of one or more participants in the communication session, the availability manager of the illustrative embodiment transmits one or more signals to a call-processing server, which then sets up the participants on the session via the appropriate communication medium such as voice, instant messaging, and so forth.

column12: Improvements in or relating to 2,6-dinitro-4-alkylphenols and carbonates thereof
column13: The invention relates to substituted dinitro phenyl alkyl carbonates of the general formula <FORM:1070755/C2/1> in which R is an alkyl group and R1 and R2 are n-alkyl groups containing from 2 to 5 carbon atoms each and together containing a total of 6 to 10 carbon atoms. Many compounds are claimed per se. The compounds may be prepared by: (1) Reacting a compound of the general formula <FORM:1070755/C2/2> in which Q represents a hydrogen or an alkali metal atom, preferably sodium or potassum with a haloformic acid ester of the formula (IV) Z.CO.OR where Z is chlorine, bromine or iodine, preferably chlorine, and R has the above-defined meaning, the reaction being effected in the presence of an acid binding agent, e.g. an alkali metal carbonate, an alkali metal bicarbonate or a tertiary amine (e.g. pyridine), where Q represents a hydrogen atom, preferably in solution in an inert organic solvent, e.g. a ketone such as acetone. The phenoxide of Formula (III) (where Q is an alkali metal) may be performed, or, preferably may be formed in situ in an inert organic solvent prior to introduction of the haloformic acid ester by reaction of the parent phenol <FORM:1070755/C2/3> with a suitable alkali metal compound, e.g. the hydroxide, carbonate or bi-carbonate. (2) The simultaneous reaction of the parent phenol (V) with a haloformic acid ester (IV) in an inert organic solvent (e.g. a ketone such as acetone) in the presence of an alkali metal carbonate or alkali metal bicarbonate, preferably an alkali metal carbonate. The haloformic acid esters (IV) may be prepared by reaction of a compound of the formula ROH with a compound of the formula COZ2 preferably in the presence of aluminium chloride as catalyst and where required in the presence of an acid binding agent. The invention also relates to the parent dinitro-alkyl phenols: <FORM:1070755/C2/4> in which R3 is a 1-n-propyl-n-butyl, 1-ethyl-n-pentyl, 1-n-butyl-pentyl, 1-n-propyl-n-hexyl, 1-n-butyl-n-hexyl, or 1-n-pentyl-n-hexyl group. Examples of compounds claimed per se are those in which R3 is 1-n-propyl-n-butyl, 1-ethyl-n-pentyl, 1-n-pentyl-n-hexyl. The compounds may be prepared by dinitration of the corresponding alkylphenols which may be prepared by reacting a p-hydroxybenzoketone with an appropriate alkylmagnesium halide, to yield a tertiary carbinol, dehydration of the carbinol, followed by catalytic hydrogenation of the resultant olefine, e.g. using palladium/charcoal in ethanol. Dehydration may occur spontaneously during heating or may be effected by the use of an acid catalyst, e.g. potassium hydrogen sulphate, p-toluene sulphonic acid or sulphuric acid. In an example, 2,6-di-nitro-4-(1-ethyl hexyl) phenyl ethyl carbonate is prepared by heating 2,6-di-nitro-4-(1-ethyl hexyl) phenol, carbonate and acetone and adding ethyl chloro formate.ALSO:Pesticidal compositions comprise as active ingredient one or more compounds of the general formula: <FORM:1070755/A5-A6/1> in which R is an alkyl group and R1 and R2 are n-alkyl groups containing from 2 to 5 carbon atoms each and together containing a total of 6 to 10 carbon atoms together with a solid or liquid diluent. Other pesticides, e.g. fungicides, acaricides or insecticides may also be incorporated. The composition may be in the form of solutions, emulsions, aerosols, pastes, dusts, wettable powders, granulates and pellets and may form thermal fumigating compositions with a solid pyrotechnic component.

column12: A method of transmitting telephone conversations data over a second call path

1,085,832. Cooling rectifiers in machines. ENGLISH ELECTRIC CO. Ltd. March 13, 1964 [March 15, 1963], No.10386/63. Heading H2A. [Also in Division H1] A semi-conductor rectifier 16 is secured to a conductive mounting- plate 22 by bonding a cup shaped member 21 of thermally - conducting electrically insulating material such as beryllium oxide to both the rectifier and the plate. The cup is fitted over a mass 20 of metal which is secured to one of the rectifier terminals 19, and its base is secured directly to the mounting plate. In the example quoted, beryllium oxide, the cup is secured to both rectifier and plate by solder, its surface first being coated with tungsten iron or molybdenum manganese. The plate 22 is intended to be secured, e.g. by bolts 23, to a heat sink 13 which may be part of the casing of a transformer (Fig. 1, not shown) or electric machine with which the rectifier is associated. In particular the machine or transformer may be in an oil-filled casing and fins on the inside of the easing wall to which the rectifier is attached may be cooled by circulation of the oil over the fins. Fig. 1 (not shown) depicts six such rectifiers attached to the outside of such a casing wall and covered by a box-like attachment (15) which may be sealed to the casing. Such an arrangement may be employed in a so-called brushless dynamo-electric machine in which the rectifiers derive from an A.C. current in one winding a D.C. current for energizing another winding.

column13: A roaster includes an upper pan including an upper side wall and an upper pan heating element inside the upper tub. The roaster further includes a lower pan connected to the upper tub, the lower pan including a lower side wall and a lower pan heating element inside the lower tub. Determining group availability on different communication media
column13: Techniques are disclosed for determining, for each candidate communication medium, the availability of one or more telecommunications endpoint users for participating in a communication session of interest (i.e., either new or existing) via the evaluated medium. In accordance with the illustrative embodiment of the present invention, an availability manager determines the availability based on (i) one or more discrete rules, or (ii) one or more continuous functions, or both. The continuous functions are specified with respect to the time that has elapsed since a previous session, the time remaining in an active session, and the expected duration of a new session. Once it has determined the availability of one or more participants in the communication session, the availability manager of the illustrative embodiment transmits one or more signals to a call-processing server, which then sets up the participants on the session via the appropriate communication medium such as voice, instant messaging, and so forth.

column12: METHOD OF MOLECULAR-SCALE PATTERN IMPRINTING AT SURFACES
column13: A method for mask-free molecular or atomic patterning of surfaces of reactive solids is disclosed. A molecular-scale pattern of adsorbate molecules is used in place of the conventional macroscopic "mask". Molecules adsorb at surfaces in patterns, governed by the structure of the surface, the chemical nature of the adsorbate, and the adsorbate coverage at the surface. The surface is patterned and then marked or imprinted with the pattern by inducing localised chemical reaction between adsorbate molecules and the surface of the solid, resulting in an imprint being formed in the vicinity of the adsorbate molecules. In one aspect of the invention, photoinduced or electron-induced reaction of the patterned adsorbate leads to patterned reaction with the surface. The reaction can take the form of patterned attachment to the surface (patterned "writing" or "doping") or patterned removal of atoms from the surface ("etching" which takes place in the initial reaction or through subsequent irradiation of the patterned surface). The adsorbate when irradiated with light, electrons or ions imprints a pattern on the substrate by localised reaction. The new method is exemplified by the case of a silicon substrate and chlorobenzene molecules which first adsorb in a pattern on a silicon crystal, and which when irradiated with light or electrons chlorinates the crystal in a similar pattern to that of the adsorbate. The presence of localised chemical reaction is demonstrated most directly by inducing reaction at a restricted locale and showing that this irradiaton-induced reaction occurs primarily at that same locale. The method is suitable for the writing, doping or etching of molecular-scale features.

column12: Method of molecular-scale pattern imprinting at surfaces
column13: A method for mask-free molecular or atomic patterning of surfaces of reactive solids is disclosed. Molecules adsorb at surfaces in patterns, governed by the structure of the surface, the chemical nature of the adsorbate, and the adsorbate coverage at the surface. The surface is patterned and then imprinted with the pattern by inducing localized chemical reaction between adsorbate molecules and the surface of the solid, resulting in an imprint being formed in the vicinity of the adsorbate molecules. When the imprinted molecular patterns are conjugated chains containing π bonds along which electrical charge can flow the molecular patterns constitute molecular wires or the imprinted molecules constitute a molecular-scale device. The surface of the substrate can be doped by including n- or p-type dopants in the adsorbate molecules. These molecular wires are anchored to the substrate by using conjugated chains which can be chemically bound at intervals along the chains to the substrates.

column13: A thermoelectric alloy composition is described comprising from 5% to 95% silicon, from 95% to 5% Germanium, from 0.01% to 0.2% lead and from 0% to 0.2% tin, all percentages being atomic percentages. In a preferred composition at least 50% silicon and 50% Germanium is present with 0.03% to 0.1 % lead and from 0 to 0.05% tin. Tin and lead in combination provide lower thermal conductivity and a greater figure of merit than with lead or tin alone. Other preferred compositions are provided and a thermoelectric material and a p-n coupling thermoelectric generator (10) incorporating the alloy is disclosed. The alloy composition provides high efficiency of power to heat loss and minimises running costs.

column12: System and method for generating personalized tag recommendations for tagging audio content
column13: Systems, methods, and computer-readable storage media for generating personalized tag recommendations using speech analytics. The system first analyzes an audio stream to identify topics in the audio stream. Next, the system identifies tags related to the topics to yield identified tags. Method of molecular-scale pattern imprinting at surfaces
column13: A method for mask-free molecular or atomic patterning of surfaces of reactive solids is disclosed. A molecular-scale pattern of adsorbate molecules is used in place of the conventional macroscopic "mask". Molecules adsorb at surfaces in patterns, governed by the structure of the surface, the chemical nature of the adsorbate, and the adsorbate coverage at the surface. The surface is patterned and then marked or imprinted with the pattern by inducing localized chemical reaction between adsorbate molecules and the surface of the solid, resulting in an imprint being formed in the vicinity of the adsorbate molecules. In one aspect of the invention, photoinduced reaction of the patterned adsorbate leads to patterned photoreaction with the surface. The photoreaction can take the form of patterned photoattachment to the surface (patterned "writing" or "doping") or patterned photoremoval of atoms from the surface ("etching" which takes place in the initial reaction or through subsequent photoirradiation of the photopatterned surface). The adsorbate when irradiated with light, electrons or ions imprints a pattern on the substrate by localised reaction. The new method is exemplified by the case of a silicon substrate and chlorobenzene molecules which first adsorb in a pattern on a silicon crystal, and which when irradiated chlorinate the crystal in a similar pattern to that of the adsorbate. The method is suitable for the writing, doping or etching of molecular-scale features.

column12: METHOD OF MOLECULAR-SCALE PATTERN IMPRINTING AT SURFACES
column13: A method for mask-free molecular or atomic patterning of surfaces of reactive solids is disclosed. Molecules adsorb at surfaces in patterns, governed by the structure of the surface, the chemical nature of the adsorbate, and the adsorbate coverage at the surface. The surface is patterned and then imprinted with the pattern by inducing localized chemical reaction between adsorbate molecules and the surface of the solid, resulting in an imprint being formed in the vicinity of the adsorbate molecules. When the imprinted molecular patterns are conjugated chains containing π bonds along which electrical charge can flow the molecular patterns constitute molecular wires or the imprinted molecules constitute a molecular-scale device. The surface of the substrate can be doped by including n - or p- type dopants in the adsorbate molecules. These molecular wires are anchored to the substrate by using conjugated chains which can be chemically bound at intervals along the chains to the substrates.

column12: METHOD OF MOLECULAR-SCALE PATTERN IMPRINTING AT SURFACES
column13: A method for mask-free molecular or atomic patterning of surfaces of reactive solids is disclosed. A molecular-scale pattern of adsorbate molecules is used in place of the conventional macroscopic 'mask'. Molecules adsorb at surfaces in patterns, governed by the structure of the surface, the chemical nature of the adsorbate, and the adsorbate coverage at the surface. The surface is patterned and then marked or imprinted with the pattern by inducing localised chemical reaction between adsorbate molecules and the surface of the solid, resulting in an imprint being formed in the vicinity of the adsorbate molecules. column13: A method may provide, by a content distribution system, access to interactive content, to a group of users and obtain a social media data indicating an interaction level of the users on a social network. The method may determine a content sharing rating for the users based on the social media data and select a user from the group based on the content sharing rating. The method may determine a recommendation for an incentive to be provided to the user within the interactive content, in exchange for the user performing an action to connect the interactive content to the user on a social network. The method may provide the recommendation to an administrative system that administers the interactive content. The method avoids the sending of an excessive number of invitations to members of a network and thereby avoids waste of network resources.

column13: According to an implementation, an application distribution system may receive a search query from a user and generate indicators of a set of applications based on the search query. The system may determine an influence rating for an entity that provided social media posts associated with one of the applications. The system may determine a sentiment rating for the content of the posts and determine a reliability rating for the entity. The reliability rating may be based the number of posts and the number of the entity's social media relationships. column12: End-to-end voice over IP streams for telephone calls established via legacy switching systems
column13: When voice over Internet Protocol (IP) capabilities are added to a conventional network of voice switches, an IP network is normally used to replace individual trunks between voice switches and to replace telephone lines between telephones and their serving voice switches. As a result, calls across the upgraded network often pass across a series of IP hops. Accordingly, the problem of replacing a series of IP hops by a single hop, to avoid degradation of end-to-end voice quality due to repeated packetization/depacketization sequences and associated functions such as compression/decompression, is addressed.

column13: 14,927. Storey, H., and Carr, J. D. June 23. Cutting ladder tapes for window blinds.-In woven ladder tapes for venetian blinds, as they come from the loom, the warps of the cross tapes cross at intervals from one main tape to the other without being intersected by weft threads. The invention consists in a machine for cutting out these unintersected warp threads. The tape is drawn through the machine by any suitable means and, by the contact of the uncut warp threads D with its teeth C, imparts rotation to the disk B, which is geared to a cam-disk F whereby the cutters are operated. The jaw J with its cutter L is first lowered between the main tapes by the action of one of the cams on the lever O; the cross warps now move up against the jaw, which is capable of a slight movement in the carriage N, parallel with the tape, under the control of a spring P<1>. The jaw K, which is likewise mounted on the carriage N and is supported by a lever Q to which is jointed a link R<2>, is now brought down to sever the threads, by the action of a cam upon a roller R at the end of the link R<2>. The cutting-device is then moved upward by the spring N' acting on the carriage N. Instead of cutters, electrically-heated wires may be used to burn through the threads.

METHOD OF MOLECULAR-SCALE PATTERN IMPRINTING AT SURFACES
column13: A method for mask-free molecular or atomic patterning of surfaces of reactive solids is disclosed. A molecular-scale pattern of adsorbate molecules is used in place of the conventional macroscopic "mask". Molecules adsorb at surfaces in patterns, governed by the structure of the surface, the chemical nature of the adsorbate, and the adsorbate coverage at the surface. The surface is patterned and then marked or imprinted with the pattern by inducing localised chemical reaction between adsorbate molecules and the surface of the solid, resulting in an imprint being formed in the vicinity of the adsorbate molecules. In one aspect of the invention, photoinduced or electron-induced reaction of the patterned adsorbate leads to patterned reaction with the surface. The reaction can take the form of patterned attachment to the surface (patterned "writing" or "doping") or patterned removal of atoms from the surface ("etching" which takes place in the initial reaction or through subsequent irradiation of the patterned surface). The adsorbate when irradiated with light, electrons or ions imprints a pattern on the substrate by localised reaction. The new method is exemplified by the case of a silicon substrate and chlorobenzene molecules which first adsorb in a pattern on a silicon crystal, and which when irradiated with light or electrons chlorinates the crystal in a similar pattern to that of the adsorbate. The presence of localised chemical reaction is demonstrated most directly by inducing reaction at a restricted locale and showing that this irradiaton-induced reaction occurs primarily at that same locale. The method is suitable for the writing, doping or etching of molecular-scale features.

Oligomeric epoxides having an average of more than one epoxy group per molecule are prepared by etherifying one mole of a polyhydric phenol with more than one mole of 2,3-epoxy-1-chloro-n-butane in the presence of an amine or a quaternary ammonium salt and subsequently reacting the etherified phenol with at least one mole of an alkali or alkaline earth hydroxide in an aqueous reaction medium. Polyhydric phenols specified are bisphenol A, hydroquinone, resorcinol, and phenol-aldehyde novolaks; amines specified are pyridine, piperidine, and tetramethyl ammonium bromide; alkalis specified are NaOH and Ca(OH)2. A water-soluble alcohol (ethanol) or ketone may be added to the reaction mixture, and the alkali is preferably added at such a rate that the pH is at or below 11. The products are soluble in methylene chloride and methyl ethyl ketone and may be cured with such agents as maleic and phthalic anhydrides, maleic acid, diethylene triamine, bis(3-amino propyl) amine and polyamides derived from polymerized linoleic acid and polyamines. Use. column12: End-to-end voice over ip streams for telephone calls established via legacy switching systems
column13: When voice over Internet Protocol (IP) capabilities are added to a conventional network of voice switches, an IP network is normally used to replace individual trunks between voice switches and to replace telephone lines between telephones and their serving voice switches. As a result, calls across the upgraded network often pass across a series of IP hops. This invention addresses the problem of replacing a series of IP hops by a single hop, to avoid degradation of end-to-end voice quality due to repeated packetization/depacketization sequences and associated functions such as compression/decompression.

column12: Method of molecular-scale pattern imprinting at surfaces
column13: A method for mask-free molecular or atomic patterning of surfaces of reactive solids is disclosed. A molecular-scale pattern of adsorbate molecules is used in place of the conventional macroscopic "mask". Molecules adsorb at surfaces in patterns, governed by the structure of the surface, the chemical nature of the adsorbate, and the adsorbate coverage at the surface. The surface is patterned and then marked or imprinted with the pattern by inducing localised chemical reaction between adsorbate molecules and the surface of the solid, resulting in an imprint being formed in the vicinity of the adsorbate molecules. In one aspect of the invention, photoinduced or electron-induced reaction of the patterned adsorbate leads to patterned reaction with the surface. The reaction can take the form of patterned attachment to the surface (patterned "writing" or "doping") or patterned removal of atoms from the surface ("etching" which takes place in the initial reaction or through subsequent irradiation of the patterned surface). The adsorbate when irradiated with light, electrons or ions imprints a pattern on the substrate by localised reaction. The new method is exemplified by the case of a silicon substrate and chlorobenzene molecules which first adsorb in a pattern on a silicon crystal, and which when irradiated with light or electrons chlorinates the crystal in a similar pattern to that of the adsorbate. The method is suitable for the writing, doping or etching of molecular-scale features. The molecular scale imprinted patterns may be used to produce quantum confinements on the surfaces of nanoscale metal or semiconductor wires or films which will result in diffraction of electrons of selected energies. Variation of voltage or illumination may be used to vary the energy of the electrons.

Rule-based system for determining user availability
column13: Techniques are disclosed for determining, for each candidate communication medium, the availability of one or more telecommunications endpoint users for participating in a communication session of interest (i.e., either new or existing) via the evaluated medium. In accordance with the illustrative embodiment of the present invention, an availability manager determines the availability based on (i) one or more discrete rules, or (ii) one or more continuous functions, or both. The continuous functions are specified with respect to the time that has elapsed since a previous session, the time remaining in an active session, and the expected duration of a new session. Once it has determined the availability of one or more participants in the communication session, the availability manager of the illustrative embodiment transmits one or more signals to a call-processing server, which then sets up the participants on the session via the appropriate communication medium such as voice, instant messaging, and so forth.

column12: Improvements relating to multi-way fluid selector valves
column13: 859,505. Valves. ENGLISH ELECTRIC CO. Ltd. Nov. 22, 1957 [Nov. 28, 1956], No. 36336/56. Class 135. A multiway fluid selector valve comprises a housing 14, a distributer member 10 having a multiplicity of ports 11 opening into the housing and having their outer ends connected by pipes to separate gas ducts (not shown), a first selector member 12 within the housing for connecting any specified number of ports to a common duct 27 and a second selector member 49 for connecting the ports of a specified group to separate individual ducts, one of which, 78, is shown in Fig. 1. The first selector comprises a rotary disc 12 carried by a shaft 15 and having " through " ports 13 common in number and spacing to the ports 11 in the distributer member 10. Slidably mounted in the selector 12 is a collector chamber 21 spring biased into engagement with the top face of the distributer member 10. The collector chamber 21 is arranged to cover four radially aligned ports in the distributer member 10 and is connected by a flexible pipe 23 to the lower end of an axially extending duct 24 in the shaft 15. The upper end of this duct communicates with a chamber 25 which is, in turn, connected by a flexible pipe 26 to a union 27 in the wall of the housing 14. By moving the selector 12 to the appropriate angular position any group of four radially aligned outlets may be connected to the union 27. The second selector 49 comprises a member, having four collector chambers 50 to 53 therein, which is mounted on a radial arm 48 attached to a hollow shaft 47. The member 49 is spring urged into contact with the upper face of the first selector 12. The ports 50 and 51 are connected to vertical ducts 55 and 56 respectively in the hollow shaft 47 by means of flexible pipes 57. The upper end of the duct 55 is connected by means of a flexible pipe 58 to an annular groove in a disc 60 arranged for rotation with the hollow shaft 47. The duct 56 is similarly connected to an annular groove 61 in the disc 60. The ports 52 and 53 are connected by flexible pipes 63 to annular grooves 64 and 65, respectively, in a further disc 66 secured to the hollow shaft 47. Interposed between the two discs 60 and 66 is a fixed disc 67. Four ducts 71 and 74 (72, 73 not being shown) in the disc 67 are arranged to lead one to each of the annular grooves in the discs 60 and 66 and each duct is connected by a flexible pipe to separate unions 76 to 79 in the casing 14, only union 78 being shown in Fig. 1. By moving the selector 49 to an appropriate angular position, any four radially aligned outlets may be connected to the unions 76 to 79. Both selectors are rotated in opposite directions by pneumatic actuators 33 and 80. The actuator 33 has a ratchet type engagement with the disc 31 which rotates the shaft 15 and hence the selector 12. The actuator 80 has a similar engagement with the disc 70 which is keyed to the hollow shaft 47 and thus rotates the second selector 49.

A mechanical hand for a robot comprises a pair of change plates each having a slot therein to receive a prong of a finger or gripper. The change plates are slidable laterally of the hand to align the slots with the prongs which may be retained in correct spaced disposition in a pallet. Locking pins are located in aligned bores in plates and have a smaller diameter part which traverses a slot in a respective prong so that when the change plates are moved laterally the larger diameter part of the pins is engaged in apertures in the prongs but will not traverse the slots and thereby the fingers or grippers are retained in the hand. The change plates are movable by means of a piston/cylinder device which may be double acting or single acting with spring return provided.

column13: A method and apparatus that provides a digital audiovisual playback system that requires only the use of a standard telecommunication device to display remotely high quality music video on-demand. The user interacts with the system via a graphic user interface (GUI) using the keypad of the telecommunication device and a communication connection through a public telephone network. The system operates in two mode of operation a Commerical Mode and a Jukebox Mode. The Commerical Mode is a continuous mode of operation and display product advertisements on a digital display device. The JukeBox Mode is initialized by the end-user calling a phone number displayed in GUI. Once a connection is established with a central database, the end-user is prompted to make music selections by using the keypad of the phone used to make the initial call. The charge for the use of the system is automatically changed to the owner of the telecommunication device.

column12: Method of molecular-scale pattern imprinting at surfaces
column13: A method for mask-free molecular or atomic patterning of surfaces of reactive solids is disclosed. Molecules adsorb at surfaces in patterns, governed by the structure of the surface, the chemical nature of the adsorbate, and the adsorbate coverage at the surface. The surface is patterned and then imprinted with the pattern by inducing localized chemical reaction between adsorbate molecules and the surface of the solid, resulting in an imprint being formed in the vicinity of the adsorbate molecules. When the imprinted molecular patterns are conjugated chains containing bonds along which electrical charge can flow the molecular patterns constitute molecular wires or the imprinted molecules constitute a molecular-scale device. The surface of the substrate can be doped by including n- or p-type dopants in the adsorbate molecules. These molecular wires are anchored to the substrate by using conjugated chains which can be chemically bound at intervals along the chains to the substrates.

column13: 1,167,725. Extruding. STANDARD TELEPHONES & CABLES Ltd. 25 Nov., 1966 [30 Nov., 1965; 7 April, 1966], Nos. 50743/65 and 15562/66. Heading B3P. A hydrostatic extrusion apparatus has a highpressure chamber 3 closed by a seal unit 2 through which the billet to be extruded passes but is free to move only when the pressure outside the seal is at least equal to the pressure in the chamber, means 21, 30 being provided to control the pressure outside the seal and second means 24 for moving the billet. The latter is a continuous rod which passes through a first seal 1 into an intermediate chamber 28 and then through the seal 2 into the high-pressure chamber 3. Both seals are formed by tapered segments of alloy steel or tungsten carbide (4), Fig. 2 (not shown), separated by layers (35) of neoprene rubber. Alternatively rubber diaphragms may be used. The seal 1 is carried by a piston 24 slidable in a housing 14 of alloy steel or cemented carbide for advancing the billet. When pressure oil is admitted through pipes 29, 30, 20 into chamber 28, seal 1 is closed against the billet and seal 2 is opened. Piston 24 is then moved forwardly to advance the billet which is extruded through die 6 by hydrostatic pressure. Release of pressure in chamber 28 closes seal 2 and opens seal 1 whereby piston 24 can be retracted. For continuous extrusion of wire a loop is maintained in the high-pressure chamber 3.

column12: Improvements in or relating to dinitrophenyl carbonates and their use as pesticides
column13: The invention relates to substituted di-nitrophenyl alkyl carbonates of the general formula <FORM:1070756/C2/1> in which R is an alkyl group containing 1 to 6 carbon atoms and R1 is 1-ethyl-n-hexyl or 1-n-propyl-n-pentyl. Compounds claimed per se are 2 - (1 - ethyl - n - hexyl) and 2-(n-propyl-n-pentyl) - 4,6 - dinitrophenyl methyl and ethyl carbonate; n-propyl, isopropyl and n-hexyl 2-(1-ethyl-n-hexyl) 4,6-dinitrophenyl carbonates. The compounds may be prepared by: (1) Reacting a compound of a general formula <FORM:1070756/C2/2> in which Q represents a hydrogen or an alkali metal atom, preferably sodium or potassium, with a haloformic acid ester of the formula (IV) Z.CO.OR where Z is chlorine, bromine or iodine, preferably chlorine, and R is as above, the reaction being effected in the presence of an acid binding agent, e.g. an alkali metal carbonate, an alkali metal bicarbonate or a tertiary amine (e.g. pyridine), where Q represents a hydrogen atom, preferably in solution in an inert organic solvent, e.g. a ketone such as acetone. The phenoxide of Formula (III) (where Q is an alkali metal) may be performed, or, preferably may be formed in situ in an inert organic solvent prior to introduction of the haloformic acid ester by reaction of the parent phenol <FORM:1070756/C2/3> with a suitable alkali metal compound, e.g. the hydroxide, carbonate or bi-carbonate. (2) The simultaneous reaction of the parent phenol (V) with a haloformic acid ester (IV) in an inert organic solvent (e.g. a ketone such as acetone) in the presence of an alkali metal carbonate or alkali metal bicarbonate, preferably an alkali metal carbonate. The haloformic acid esters (IV) may be prepared by reaction of a compound of the formula ROH with a compound of the formula COZ2 preferably in the presence of aluminium chloride as catalyst and where required in the presence of an acid binding agent. The parent dinitro-alkyl phenols (V), where R1 is as above, may be prepared by dinitration of the corresponding alkylphenols. The latter may be prepared by reacting a o-hydroxybenzoketone with an appropriate alkylmagnesium halide, to yield a tertiary carbinol, dehydration of the carbinol, followed by catalytic hydrogenation of the resultant olefine, e.g. using palladium/charcoal in ethanol. Dehydration may occur spontaneously during heating or may be effected by the use of an acid catalyst, e.g. potassium hydrogen sulphate, p-toluene sulphonic acid or sulphuric acid. In an example 2 - (1 - ethyl - n - hexyl) - 4,6 - dinitro phenyl ethyl carbonate is prepared by heating 2-(1-ethyl-n-hexyl)-4,6-dinitro phenol, potassium carbonate and acetone and adding thereto ethyl chloroformate.ALSO:Pesticidal compositions comprise as active ingredient one or more compounds of a general formula: <FORM:1070756/A5-A6/1> in which R is an alkyl group containing one to six carbon atoms and R1 represents 1-ethyl-n-hexyl or 1-n-propyl-n-pentyl together with solid or liquid carriers or diluents. Other pesticides e.g. fungicides, acaricides or insecticides may also be incorporated. The composition may be in the form of solutions or emulsions, aerosols, pastes, dusts, wettable powders, granulates and pellets and may form thermal fumigating compositions with a solid pyrotechnic component.

column12: RAPID PRECIPITATION-DRIVEN KILOBASE SIZE SELECTION OF HMW DNA
column13: Provided herein are methods of purifying a sample containing nucleic acids to obtain isolated nucleic acids of a desired size range and methods of sequencing nucleic acids of a desired size range. The methods include a) combining a nucleic acid-containing sample with a precipitation buffer in a container to provide a precipitation mixture in which the precipitation buffer comprises water, a buffer, a salt, and polyvinyl pyrrolidinone (PVP) and/or Ficoll. The methods also include precipitating the nucleic acids in the precipitation mixture to provide a precipitated nucleic acid portion and a remaining sample portion. The precipitated nucleic acid portion predominantly comprises nucleic acid molecules above a selected size cutoff value and the remaining sample portion predominantly comprises nucleic acid molecules below the selected size cutoff value. The methods also include separating the precipitated nucleic acid portion from the remaining sample portion. Related compositions and kits are also provided herein.

A thermoelectric alloy composition is described comprising from 5% to 95% silicon, from 95% to 5% Germanium, from 0.01% to 0.2% lead and from 0% to 0.2% tin, all percentages being atomic percentages. In a preferred composition at least 50% silicon and 50% Germanium is present with 0.03% to 0.1 % lead and from 0 to 0.05% tin. Tin and lead in combination provide lower thermal conductivity and a greater figure of merit than with lead or tin alone. Other preferred compositions are provided and a thermoelectric material and a p-n coupling thermoelectric generator (10) incorporating the alloy is disclosed. The alloy composition provides high efficiency of power to heat loss and minimises running costs.

column13: When voice over Internet Protocol (IP) capabilities are added to a conventional network of voice switches, an IP network is normally used to replace individual trunks between voice switches and to replace telephone lines between telephones and their serving voice switches. As a result, calls across the upgraded network often pass across a series of IP hops. This invention addresses the problem of replacing a series of IP hops by a single hop, to avoid degradation of end-to-end voice quality due to repeated packetization/depacketization sequences and associated functions such as compression/decompression.

column12: METHOD OF MOLECULAR-SCALE PATTERN IMPRINTING AT SURFACES
column13: A method for mask-free molecular or atomic patterning of surfaces of reactive solids is disclosed. Molecules adsorb at surfaces in patterns, governed by the structure of the surface, the chemical nature of the adsorbate, and the adsorbate coverage at the surface. The surface is patterned and then imprinted with the pattern by inducing localized chemical reaction between adsorbate molecules and the surface of the solid, resulting in an imprint being formed in the vicinity of the adsorbate molecules. When the imprinted molecular patterns are conjugated chains containing .pi. bonds along which electrical charge can flow the molecular patterns constitute molecular wires or the imprinted molecules constitute a molecular-scale device. The surface of the substrate can be doped by including n - or p- type dopants in the adsorbate molecules. These molecular wires are anchored to the substrate by using conjugated chains which can be chemically bound at intervals along the chains to the substrates.

column12: Optical head with monolithic layer for optical storage
column13: Optical heads having a monolithic layer for interfacing storage media and methods for manufacturing such heads. In one embodiment, the substrate has first and second surfaces to define a through hole which forms an optical path and a lens with a spherical surface and a flat surface opposing the spherical surface is disposed in the optical path in the through hole. The flat surface is coplanar with a flat portion of the second surface. The optical head also includes a transparent layer contiguously formed over both the flat surface of the lens and the second surface of the substrate to form a monolithic layer. The refractive index of the additional layer may match that of the lens. In addition, the additional layer may have a material hardness greater than that of the lens to protect the lens and to reduce wear.

column12: APPARATUS FOR EFFICIENTLY DETERMINING INSTRUCTION LENGTH WITHIN A STREAM OF X86 INSTRUCTION BYTES
column13: An apparatus efficiently determines the length of an instruction within a stream of instruction bytes processed by a microprocessor having a variable instruction length instruction set architecture. The apparatus includes combinatorial logic associated with each instruction byte of the stream, each configured to receive the associated instruction byte and the next instruction byte of the stream and to generate in response thereto a first length, a second length, and a select control. A multiplexor associated with each of the combinatorial logic selects and outputs one of the following inputs based on the select control received from the combinatorial logic: a zero input and the second length received from the combinatorial logic associated with each of the next three instruction bytes of the stream. An adder associated with each of the combinatorial logic and multiplexor adds the first length and the output of the multiplexor to generate the length of the instruction.

The design allows for a shorted stator, where the armature magnets are controlled to reciprocate to a greater maximum displacement than for a equivalent conventional linear motor. The control strategy is such that a minimum of external sensors are required. The linear motor is driven at its resonant frequency ensuring optionally efficient operation. A determination of the maximum current is made based on a relationship with the resonant frequency and the evaporating temperature/pressure of the vapour entering the compressor. The current is then limited to control the maximum displacement to avoid damage

column12: Improvements in battery operated electric machines
column13: There is disclosed a lawn or grass mower having a cutting mechanism (14) driven by an electric motor (10), the electric motor (10) being powered by a rechargeable lead acid batter (11), the battery (11) being protected against damage caused as a result of over rapid discharge by control means (13). The control means (13) is able to sequentially sample battery voltage discharge levels and to determine when the sampled battery voltage discharge level drops rapidly at a rate higher than normal operational voltage level drop. A disabling means (14) is arranged to disable said battery means (11) from said mower (40) if the voltage discharge level of said battery means (11) does not return to a voltage level greater than a control level being a preset differential (ΔV) below said reference voltage level (V ref) within a predetermined period of time (ΔT).

1,105,750. Rectifying. ENGLISH ELECTRIC CO. Ltd. 17 Dec., 1965 [22 Dec., 1964], No. 52061/64. Heading H2F. In a rectifying arrangement, as shown a polyphase bridge of controllable rectifiers 13R, 13Y, 13B, 14R, 14Y, 14B, auxiliary commutating rectifiers 18, 19, and capacitors 20 are provided to shut-off a conducting rectifier before natural commutation. Thus, both initiation and extinction of conduction are provided to allow for control of both output voltage and power factor. If, for example, the conducting period is arranged to be symmetrical with respect to the maximum voltage in a half wave, then a power factor of unity obtains. Varying the width of this period varies the mean output voltage. Displacing the conducting period forwards within the half cycle gives a leading power factor, and displacing it backwards a lagging power factor. As shown, diodes 15, 16 are provided to complete a current path back to the neutral point of N of transformer 10, as an alternative to a path through two main rectifiers 13, 14. A sequence of operations for the Red phase is as follows: With R negative rectifier 14R is fired and a path is completed through 14R, load 12 and diode 15 and/or either or both of rectifiers 13Y, 13B. At the end of the desired period 19R is fired discharging a capacitor 20 (previously charged with terminal 20A positive) to shut off Rectifier 19R continues to conduct until capacitor 20 is again charged with terminal 20B now positive. Subsequently, during the next half cycle when R is positive, rectifier 13R is fired and current flows through 13R, load 12 and diode 16 and/or either or both rectifiers 14Y, 14B. At the end of the desired period 18R conducts to discharge capacitor 20 through rectifier 13R to shut it off. A similar sequence applies to the yellow and blue phases.

column12: Clutch control system with warning of incorrect drive-off gear selection
column13: A clutch control system for the automatic control of a motor vehicle clutch which connects an engine with a gearbox under the control of a driver operated gear ratio selector lever. The control system controls both initial clutch take-up on starting of the vehicle, clutch re-engagement following each ratio change, clutch disengagement on movement of the gear selector lever to change the operative ratio of the gearbox, and clutch disengagement on the coming to rest of the vehicle. The clutch control system also warns (50.c) the operator if he attempts to drive away in a designated non take-up gear or in any gear in a predetermined abusive manner and may be arranged to promote rapid engagement or disengagement of the clutch in certain abusive conditions to reduce energy generation in the clutch.

Ein beispielhaftes Verfahren erhält eine Vielzahl von Eingangswerten in Zusammenhang mit der Dampferzeugung und verwendet eine modellprädiktive Steuerung, um einen ersten Wert in Zusammenhang mit der Voraussage einer Menge eines ersten Brennstoffs und einen zweiten Wert in Zusammenhang mit der Voraussage einer Menge eines zweiten Brennstoffs zur Erzeugung einer Dampfmenge zu bestimmen. Brennstoffzufuhrraten des ersten und des zweiten Brennstoffs werden anschließend auf der Grundlage der ersten und zweiten Bahnführungswerte gesteuert.

column12: Sistema y procedimiento de evaluación de indentación de colchones
column13: Sistema para medir simultáneamente las propiedades de dureza de indentación, las propiedades de extensión y las propiedades de elasticidad de un colchón (8), que comprende unos primeros medios de indentación (2) y unos segundos medios de indentación (2), y unos medios para empujar los primeros medios de indentación (2) y los segundos medios de indentación (2) en el colchón (8) con una fuerza predeterminada, y comprendiendo también unos medios láser para proyectar una línea láser (9) sobre la superficie del colchón que se extiende entre los primeros medios de indentación (2) y los segundos medios de indentación (2) y configurados para mapear la amplitud, la forma y la dependencia temporal de la deflexión resultante de la superficie del colchón entre los primeros medios de indentación (2) y los segundos medios de indentación (2).

PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a piezoelectric scanner which is so structured as not to be affected by an external force. SOLUTION: A piezoelectric scanner 1 is equipped with four piezoelectric elements 4a to 4b which are joined to a base member 2 and attached to a scanned member 7 through corresponding joints 6a to 6d. The piezoelectric elements 4a to 4d are each provided with two piezoelectric material layers which are arranged confronting each other so as to be joined together when a voltage is applied between the material layers. The four piezoelectric elements 4a to 4d are so connected as to be deflected inwards or outwards all together. The joints 6a and 6d are fitted to the member 7 so as to be located below the joints 6b and 6c, because a voltage is applied to the elements 4a to 4d to rotate the member 7. The center of gravity of the member 7 is located on a rotation axis, so that a scanner of this constitution is less affected by an external vibrations than a previously designed one.

column12: Apparatus and a method in a microprocessor
column13: The present invention, in one embodiment, is directed to an apparatus and method in a microprocessor that has an instruction set architecture in which instructions may include a length-modifying prefix used to select an address/operand size other than a default address/operand size, the apparatus configured to mark the start byte and the end byte of each instruction in a stream of instruction bytes. Another embodiment discloses, in a microprocessor that has an instruction set architecture in which the instructions may include a variable number of prefix bytes, an apparatus and method for efficiently extracting instructions from a stream of undifferentiated instruction bytes. A further embodiment discloses an apparatus and method for efficiently determining the length of an instruction within a stream of instruction bytes processed by a microprocessor having a variable instruction length instruction set architecture.

Embodiments of the present invention provide a structure comprising: a flux guide comprising a plurality of resonant circuit elements (110, 120, 310F) each element comprising an electrically conductive loop portion (112, 122), opposed ends of the loop portion (112, 122) being coupled to one another through a capacitive element (114, 124), adjacent resonant elements of the flux guide (115, 315) being arranged to be magneto-inductively coupled to one another thereby to allow a magneto-inductive (MI) wave to be supported by the guide (115, 315), wherein at least one of the resonant elements (1205) is switchable between a first condition in which the element is arranged to support propagation of an MI wave along the waveguide and a second condition in which the element is arranged to prevent propagation of an MI wave along the waveguide.

column13: This invention relates to high power linear amplifiers. A high power linear amplifier is disclosed for communications such as CDMA communication systems. Linear amplifiers as used in communication systems exhibit a linear characteristic where the amplifiers output power increases relative to an input power. After a certain input level, known as a gain saturation point, the amplifier then exhibits non-linear characteristics; the output power increases relatively little with respect to power input. This non-linear region is also known as the saturation region or the gain compression region. In accordance with the invention, there is provided a power amplifier comprising a power amplifier, a feedback circuit and a control element; wherein the feedback circuit receives a sample of the input signal delayed in time and employs phase and amplitude components of both the input signal delayed in time and a feedback signal derived from the output of the power amplifier to drive a control element, which control element determines the signal input to the amplifier whereby the power amplifier can produce an improved linear output.

DISPOSITIVO PARA CONTENER ENVASE TIPO BLISTER.
column13: Se presenta un dispositivo para sujetar paquetes alveolados que tiene un primer y un segundo miembro, que funcionan entre una condición abierta que permite la extracción de los productos de los paquetes alveolados y una condición cerrado que evita su extracción. Los paquetes alveolados no se pueden sacar del dispositivo. Los paquetes alveolados pueden estar sujetos por paneles que se superponen a sus bases. Los miembros pueden retenidos en su condición cerrada mediante un cierre a prueba de niños.

A unified wallet manager (UWM) virtualized as a single virtual service in which all transactions relative to the UWM are treated as immutable facts permanently stored in append-only queues or ledgers from the time of their creation. A rules engine reads conversion requests in request calls to the service and determines which rule or rules, including responsible gaming rules, to apply to control or convert funds from one ledger to another, in the same or different vertically scaled gaming systems. The UWM is a peer of other vertical gaming systems, and the gaming systems access the UWM via an API server and data egresses from the UWM through an ETL process from a database cluster. The ledger stores funds of many different types, including real money, points, play money, and others. Third parties can integrate with the UWM through an integration hub connected to the UWM.

column12: SYSTEM FOR SIMPLIFICATION OF RECONFIGURABLE BEAM-FORMING NETWORK PROCESSING WITHIN A PHASED ARRAY ANTENNA FOR A TELECOMMUNICATIONS SATELLITE
column13: A telecommunications satellite having a phased array antenna, wherein the beam-forming function within the phased array is simplified by partitioning it into two stages, in which the sub-array stage relates to a fixed, or infrequently changed,set of overlapping sub-arrays and the main stage provides the main pattern reconfiguration, typically in the form of multiple reconfigurable spot beams within a defined coverage region. The key advantage lies in the significant reduction in number of second stage beam-forming control points (at which independent amplitude and phase is applied) when compared with a conventional phased array (where amplitude and phase control is applied for each element of the array). The sub-array stage beam-forming may be implemented in analogue technology. The main beam-former may be implemented in digital technology, where the key processing functions of A/D or D/A conversion, frequency (de)multiplexing and digital beam-forming all scale with the number of control points.
